{"title_page": "R (March) v Secretary of State for Health", "text_new": "{{coi|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|UK judicial review quashing a decision on the grounds of material error of fact}}\n{{italic title|all=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox court case\n| name = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health\n| image = \n| court = High Court\n| date decided = 16 April 2010\n| full name = The Queen (on the application of Andrew Michael March) v The Secretary of State for Health\n| citations = [2010] [https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html EWHC 765 (Admin)]\n| judges = [[James Holman (judge)|Mr Justice Holman]]\n| prior actions =  \n| subsequent actions = \n| opinions = \n| transcripts =\n| keywords = Material error of fact; Relevance of Hansard\n}}\n\n'''''R (March) v Secretary of State for Health''''' was a successful 2010 [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] which challenged the UK [[Department of Health and Social Care|Department of Health's]] decision not to implement Recommendation 6(h) of the Archer Independent Inquiry.<ref name=\"Bailii1\">{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57}}</ref> \nThe case was important in developing the doctrine of ''error of fact'' in [[public law]] which previously had not readily been the subject of judicial intervention.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=2008 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Fifth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=468 |isbn=9781841138244 |quote= ''Judicial review judges have traditionally been cautious about fact-based challenges''.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Demetriou |first1=Marie |last2= Houseman |first2= Stephen |date= 1997|title=Review for Error of Fact\u2014A Brief Guide |url= https://doi.org/10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 |journal=JR |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201332 |doi= 10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 | publisher = Routledge |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants= E v. Secretary of State for the Home Department  |vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 |pinpoint=51 |court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html}}</ref>\n\n==Facts==\n\n[[Andrew March|Andrew Michael March]], a [[haemophilia|haemophiliac]],<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |last1= Meikle |first1= James  |date= 2010-04-16 |title= Court ruling may help contaminated blood victims win higher payouts|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote= ''A classical music composer who was infected by HIV when he was nine, who later developed hepatitis, won a judicial review that challenged the basis of health ministers' decision last year not to increase the payments.''}}</ref> along with several thousand other patients was treated with contaminated blood products in the 1970\u2032s and 1980\u2032s.<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |date= 2010-04-16 |title=Composer wins compensation review over contaminated blood |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote=An award-winning composer who contracted HIV and Hepatitis C through NHS treatment with contaminated blood products has won a legal challenge over compensation payments.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood and blood products]] disaster also occurred in the [[Republic of Ireland]]<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /> and various compensation schemes and statutory provisions were put in place between 1991 and 2002 on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the state.<ref name=\"Hynes1\">{{cite letter| first = Lara| last = Hynes| recipient = Mark A. Ward| subject = RE: Blood & Tissue Policy Division, (DOHC)| language = English| date = {{date|2009-07-30|mdy}}| quote =''The scheme of compensation for persons with haemophilia was put in place on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the State''}}</ref> However, the level of payments made to similarly infected and affected people in the Republic of Ireland was considerably greater than payments made to victims in the United Kingdom. In the UK, the Department of Health had consistently refused to increase the ''[[ex gratia]]'' support payments to be on a par with the more generous levels of payments made in the Republic of Ireland, arguing that [[Legal liability|liability]] in the UK had never been established, whilst in Ireland there had been findings of fault.<ref name=\"Guardian1\" /><ref>{{Cite Hansard|jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Topical Questions |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2009-06-23/debates/b27195ce-b353-48b1-b120-8b64dbd4470d/CommonsChamber |date=June 23, 2009 |volume=494 |column=656 |speaker= Gillian Merron |position= Minister of State at the Department of Health}}</ref> This was found to be incorrect since the basis behind the Irish scheme was compassion, not fault.<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Independent Public Inquiry Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=9 |page=89 |access-date=2010-04-12 |quote=''The payments by the Irish Government were equally made without an admission of liability.''}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57 |paras = [27] [30] [34]}}</ref>\n\nThe ministerial decision at the centre of this judicial review hinged on the refusal to adopt a key recommendation of the independent, non-statutory Archer Inquiry.<ref>{{cite court |litigants= R (March) v Secretary of State for Health |vol=765 |reporter=BMLR |opinion=116 |pinpoint=19 |court=EWHC (Admin) |date=2010 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote= ''...that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h);''}}</ref> In particular, the Minister rejected Recommendation 6(h), which read as follows: ''\u2033We suggest that payments should be at least the equivalent of those payable under the scheme which applies at any time in Ireland.\u2033''<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Independent Public Inquiry Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=12 |page=107-110 |access-date=2010-04-11 |quote=''We believe that the following recommendations would help to meet the unmet needs of patients with haemophilia and their families...''}}</ref>\n\n==Judgment==\n\nThe judgement was handed down in Court 49 of the High Court by Mr Justice Holman on Friday, 16th April 2010, the eve of World Haemophilia Day 2010. {{quote box |width=30%|style=min-width:12em|''The thrust of the case on behalf of the claimant is that the answers given by the minister on 23 June and 1 July, when considered separately or cumulatively, reveal a material error of fact on the part of the government as to the situation in Ireland; that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h); and, accordingly, that the government should be required to reconsider their response to recommendation 6 (h)''.|source=\u2014 Mr Justice Holman<ref name=\"Bailii1\"/>}}\n\n===Material error of fact===\nThe ''March'' case demonstrates that the jurisdiction of the court extends to quashing a decision if the published reasons for the decision contain an error which is considered capable of making a material difference to the outcome of the decision had the error in question not been made.<ref>{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |date= June 2011 |title= Administrative Law |edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ |location=Oxford |publisher= Oxford University Press |page=333 |chapter=9.2.3 |isbn=9780199601752 |quote=''An error of fact revolution?''}}</ref> The sequence of events in Ireland were critical to this case. The Irish government had decided to make payments at a substantial level, very much like compensation, but strictly speaking ''ex gratia'' in nature, and they decided to do this before there was any finding of fault.<ref name=\"Hynes1\" />  It was the Westminster government\u2019s stance on this that propagated the error.\n\nThere are a number of conditions which need to be met in order for the court to intervene: \n{{bulleted list |There must be a demonstrable error to an existing fact;<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=511 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''But the claimant must demonstrate that (i) there is an error of fact;''}},</ref> |The error needs to be sufficiently established;<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.lexology.com/library/document.ashx?g=35c99556-a759-44fe-b12f-94ba54b72469 |title= Quashing a decision on the basis of material error of fact.''|last1= Lidbetter |first1= Andrew |last2= Zar |first2= Nusrat |last3= Condliffe |first3=Anna |publisher= Herbert Smith Freehills LLP|date=30 April 2010 |website=www.lexology.com |access-date=11 April 2020 |quote=...the fact or evidence must have been \u2033established\u2033, in the sense that it was uncontentious and objectively verifiable;}}</ref> | The claimant and their legal advisors must not have been party to the error;<ref>{{cite court |litigants= E v. Secretary of State for the Home Department  |vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 |pinpoint=66 |court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote=''Thirdly, the appellant (or his advisers) must not been have been responsible for the mistake.''}}</ref> | The error of fact needs to be \u2033material\u2033; in that there could have been an alternative decision \u2033but for the error\u2033.<ref>{{cite court |litigants= R (March) v Secretary of State for Health |vol=765 |reporter=BMLR |opinion=116 |pinpoint=53 |court=EWHC (Admin) |date=2010 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote=''In my view, the error is material because a different decision might (I stress, might) have been made if the government had correctly focussed on, and grappled with, the compassionate basis of Irish payments, when considering in particular the passage at internal pages 90 \u2013 94 of Archer which underpins recommendation 6 (h).''}}</ref>}}\n\n==Significance==\nOn the morning the judgment was handed down, the late [[Alf Morris|Lord Morris of Manchester]] described how he felt the decision was historic for the haemophilia community and how he expected it would be welcomed by the community of some 5,000 people who were infected ''en masse'' with HIV and Hepatitis C through contaminated blood and blood products.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/mobile/health/8624879.stm |title=Campaigner wins tainted blood case |date=16 April 2010 |website=BBC News |access-date= 2020-04-12}}</ref> Lord Morris said:\n<blockquote>''\u20261,974 have died in direct consequence of the NHS treatment. Yet until today the legal road to redress was blocked, just as unbreakably as any prospect of securing justice by legislative means. Now with today\u2019s historic breakthrough in the High Court and the huge public backing for my Contaminated Blood Support for Infected and Bereaved Persons Bill, both roads are open. Our determination to ensure that \u2032right is done\u2032 is totally vindicated and a just outcome is now in sight.''</blockquote>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Fordham|first=Michael|title=Judicial Review Handbook|publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |date=2012|edition=6th|isbn=9781849461597}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clements|first=Richard|title=Public Law\u2014Blackstone\u2032s questions & answers|publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2015|edition=Eighth|isbn=9780198715733}}\n*{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |title= Administrative Law |date= 2011|edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA333&ots=fISK8plf4X&dq=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&f=false |publisher= Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199601752}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Abrogation in Public Law]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Law-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Common law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom public law]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judicial review]]\n", "text_old": "{{coi|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|UK judicial review quashing a decision on the grounds of material error of fact}}\n{{italic title|all=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox court case\n| name = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health\n| image = \n| court = High Court\n| date decided = 16 April 2010\n| full name = The Queen (on the application of Andrew Michael March) v The Secretary of State for Health\n| citations = [2010] [https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html EWHC 765 (Admin)]\n| judges = [[James Holman (judge)|Mr Justice Holman]]\n| prior actions =  \n| subsequent actions = \n| opinions = \n| transcripts =\n| keywords = Material error of fact; Relevance of Hansard\n}}\n\n'''''R (March) v Secretary of State for Health''''' was a successful 2010 [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] which challenged the UK [[Department of Health and Social Care|Department of Health's]] decision not to implement Recommendation 6(h) of the Archer Independent Inquiry.<ref name=\"Bailii1\">{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57}}</ref> \nThe case was important in developing the doctrine of ''error of fact'' in [[public law]] which previously had not readily been the subject of judicial intervention.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=2008 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Fifth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=468 |isbn=9781841138244 |quote= ''Judicial review judges have traditionally been cautious about fact-based challenges''.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Demetriou |first1=Marie |last2= Houseman |first2= Stephen |date= 1997|title=Review for Error of Fact\u2014A Brief Guide |url= https://doi.org/10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 |journal=JR |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201332 |doi= 10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 | publisher = Routledge |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants= E v. Secretary of State for the Home Department  |vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 |pinpoint=51 |court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html}}</ref>\n\n==Facts==\n\n[[Andrew March|Andrew Michael March]], a [[haemophilia|haemophiliac]],<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |last1= Meikle |first1= James  |date= 2010-04-16 |title= Court ruling may help contaminated blood victims win higher payouts|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote= ''A classical music composer who was infected by HIV when he was nine, who later developed hepatitis, won a judicial review that challenged the basis of health ministers' decision last year not to increase the payments.''}}</ref> along with several thousand other patients was treated with contaminated blood products in the 1970\u2032s and 1980\u2032s.<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |date= 2010-04-16 |title=Composer wins compensation review over contaminated blood |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote=An award-winning composer who contracted HIV and Hepatitis C through NHS treatment with contaminated blood products has won a legal challenge over compensation payments.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood and blood products]] disaster also occurred in the [[Republic of Ireland]]<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /> and various compensation schemes and statutory provisions were put in place between 1991 and 2002 on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the state.<ref name=\"Hynes1\">{{cite letter| first = Lara| last = Hynes| recipient = Mark A. Ward| subject = RE: Blood & Tissue Policy Division, (DOHC)| language = English| date = {{date|2009-07-30|mdy}}| quote =''The scheme of compensation for persons with haemophilia was put in place on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the State''}}</ref> However, the level of payments made to similarly infected and affected people in the Republic of Ireland was considerably greater than payments made to victims in the United Kingdom. In the UK, the Department of Health had consistently refused to increase the ''[[ex gratia]]'' support payments to be on a par with the more generous levels of payments made in the Republic of Ireland, arguing that [[Legal liability|liability]] in the UK had never been established, whilst in Ireland there had been findings of fault.<ref name=\"Guardian1\" /><ref>{{Cite Hansard|jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Topical Questions |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2009-06-23/debates/b27195ce-b353-48b1-b120-8b64dbd4470d/CommonsChamber |date=June 23, 2009 |volume=494 |column=656 |speaker= Gillian Merron |position= Minister of State at the Department of Health}}</ref> This was found to be incorrect since the basis behind the Irish scheme was compassion, not fault.<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Archer Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=9 |page=89 |access-date=2010-04-12 |quote=''The payments by the Irish Government were equally made without an admission of liability.''}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57 |paras = [27] [30] [34]}}</ref>\n\nThe ministerial decision at the centre of this judicial review hinged on the refusal to adopt a key recommendation of the independent, non-statutory Archer Inquiry.<ref>{{cite court |litigants= R (March) v Secretary of State for Health |vol=765 |reporter=BMLR |opinion=116 |pinpoint=19 |court=EWHC (Admin) |date=2010 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote= ''...that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h);''}}</ref> In particular, the Minister rejected Recommendation 6(h), which read as follows: ''\u2033We suggest that payments should be at least the equivalent of those payable under the scheme which applies at any time in Ireland.\u2033''<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Archer Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=12 |page=107-110 |access-date=2010-04-11 |quote=''We believe that the following recommendations would help to meet the unmet needs of patients with haemophilia and their families...''}}</ref>\n\n==Judgment==\n\nThe judgement was handed down in Court 49 of the High Court by Mr Justice Holman on Friday, 16th April 2010, the eve of World Haemophilia Day 2010. {{quote box |width=30%|style=min-width:12em|''The thrust of the case on behalf of the claimant is that the answers given by the minister on 23 June and 1 July, when considered separately or cumulatively, reveal a material error of fact on the part of the government as to the situation in Ireland; that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h); and, accordingly, that the government should be required to reconsider their response to recommendation 6 (h)''.|source=\u2014 Mr Justice Holman<ref name=\"Bailii1\"/>}}\n\n===Material error of fact===\nThe ''March'' case demonstrates that the jurisdiction of the court extends to quashing a decision if the published reasons for the decision contain an error which is considered capable of making a material difference to the outcome of the decision had the error in question not been made.<ref>{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |date= June 2011 |title= Administrative Law |edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ |location=Oxford |publisher= Oxford University Press |page=333 |chapter=9.2.3 |isbn=9780199601752 |quote=''An error of fact revolution?''}}</ref> The sequence of events in Ireland were critical to this case. The Irish government had decided to make payments at a substantial level, very much like compensation, but strictly speaking ''ex gratia'' in nature, and they decided to do this before there was any finding of fault.<ref name=\"Hynes1\" />  It was the Westminster government\u2019s stance on this that propagated the error.\n\nThere are a number of conditions which need to be met in order for the court to intervene: \n{{bulleted list |There must be a demonstrable error to an existing fact;<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=511 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''But the claimant must demonstrate that (i) there is an error of fact;''}},</ref> |The error needs to be sufficiently established;<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.lexology.com/library/document.ashx?g=35c99556-a759-44fe-b12f-94ba54b72469 |title= Quashing a decision on the basis of material error of fact.''|last1= Lidbetter |first1= Andrew |last2= Zar |first2= Nusrat |last3= Condliffe |first3=Anna |publisher= Herbert Smith Freehills LLP|date=30 April 2010 |website=www.lexology.com |access-date=11 April 2020 |quote=...the fact or evidence must have been \u2033established\u2033, in the sense that it was uncontentious and objectively verifiable;}}</ref> | The claimant and their legal advisors must not have been party to the error;<ref>{{cite court |litigants= E v. Secretary of State for the Home Department  |vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 |pinpoint=66 |court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote=''Thirdly, the appellant (or his advisers) must not been have been responsible for the mistake.''}}</ref> | The error of fact needs to be \u2033material\u2033; in that there could have been an alternative decision \u2033but for the error\u2033.<ref>{{cite court |litigants= R (March) v Secretary of State for Health |vol=765 |reporter=BMLR |opinion=116 |pinpoint=53 |court=EWHC (Admin) |date=2010 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote=''In my view, the error is material because a different decision might (I stress, might) have been made if the government had correctly focussed on, and grappled with, the compassionate basis of Irish payments, when considering in particular the passage at internal pages 90 \u2013 94 of Archer which underpins recommendation 6 (h).''}}</ref>}}\n\n==Significance==\nOn the morning the judgment was handed down, the late [[Alf Morris|Lord Morris of Manchester]] described how he felt the decision was historic for the haemophilia community and how he expected it would be welcomed by the community of some 5,000 people who were infected ''en masse'' with HIV and Hepatitis C through contaminated blood and blood products.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/mobile/health/8624879.stm |title=Campaigner wins tainted blood case |date=16 April 2010 |website=BBC News |access-date= 2020-04-12}}</ref> Lord Morris said:\n<blockquote>''\u20261,974 have died in direct consequence of the NHS treatment. Yet until today the legal road to redress was blocked, just as unbreakably as any prospect of securing justice by legislative means. Now with today\u2019s historic breakthrough in the High Court and the huge public backing for my Contaminated Blood Support for Infected and Bereaved Persons Bill, both roads are open. Our determination to ensure that \u2032right is done\u2032 is totally vindicated and a just outcome is now in sight.''</blockquote>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Fordham|first=Michael|title=Judicial Review Handbook|publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |date=2012|edition=6th|isbn=9781849461597}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clements|first=Richard|title=Public Law\u2014Blackstone\u2032s questions & answers|publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2015|edition=Eighth|isbn=9780198715733}}\n*{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |title= Administrative Law |date= 2011|edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA333&ots=fISK8plf4X&dq=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&f=false |publisher= Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199601752}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Abrogation in Public Law]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Law-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Common law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom public law]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judicial review]]\n", "name_user": "SpookiePuppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFacts:Amending reference 9 and 12 (Archer Report title) to \"Independent Public Inquiry Report\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R_(March)_v_Secretary_of_State_for_Health"}
{"title_page": "Pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{short description|Longest word in the English language published in a dictionary}}\n{{About|the term used to describe a form of occupational lung disease|the article about the disease itself|Silicosis}}\n'''''Pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis''''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-us-pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis.ogg|\u02cc|nj|u\u02d0|m|\u0259|n|o\u028a|\u02cc|\u028c|l|t|r|\u0259|\u02cc|m|a\u026a|k|r|\u0259|\u02c8|s|k|\u0252|p|\u026a|k|\u02cc|s|\u026a|l|\u026a|k|o\u028a|v|\u0252|l|\u02cc|k|e\u026a|n|o\u028a|\u02cc|k|o\u028a|n|i|\u02c8|o\u028a|s|\u026a|s}}{{refn|{{OxfordDictionaries.com|accessdate=2017-10-10|Pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis}}}}{{refn|{{MerriamWebsterDictionary|Pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis}}}}) is a word coined by the president of the [[National Puzzlers' League]] as a [[synonym]] for the disease known as [[silicosis]]. It is the [[longest word in the English language]] published in a dictionary, the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', which defines it as \"an artificial long word said to mean a lung disease caused by inhaling very fine ash and sand dust\".<ref>{{cite web |work=Oxford Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |url=http://oxforddictionaries.com/view/entry/m_en_gb0642240#m_en_gb0642240 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719114141/http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis |archivedate=2012-07-19 |title=Definition of {{shy|pneumono|ultra|microscopic|silico|volcano|coniosis}} in Oxford dictionary (British and World English) }}</ref>\n\nSilicosis is a form of occupational lung disease caused by inhalation of crystalline silica dust, and is marked by inflammation and scarring in the form of nodular lesions in the upper lobes of the lungs (which you can die from). It is a type of [[pneumoconiosis]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThis word was invented in the annual meeting of the [[National Puzzlers' League]] (N.P.L.) by its president Everett M. Smith. The word featured in the headline for an article published by the ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]'' on February 23, 1935, titled \"Puzzlers Open 103rd Session Here by Recognizing 45-Letter Word\":\n\n<blockquote>{{shy|Pneumono|ultra|microscopic|silico|volcano|coniosis}} succeeded electrophotomicrographically as the longest word in the English language recognized by the National Puzzlers' League at the opening session of the organization's 103rd semi-annual meeting held yesterday at the Hotel New Yorker. The puzzlers explained that the forty-five-letter word is the synonym of a special form of [[pneumoconiosis]] caused by ultra-microscopic particles of silica [[Volcanic ash|volcanic dust]]...</blockquote>\n\nSubsequently, the word was used in a puzzle book, ''Bedside Manna'', after which time, members of the N.P.L. campaigned to include the word in major dictionaries.<ref>\n{{cite book\n | last = Cole\n | first = Chris\n | title = Wordplay, A Curious Dictionary of Language Oddities\n | publisher = Sterling Publishing Co., Inc.\n | year = 1999\n | pages = 106\u2013107\n | isbn = 0-8069-1797-0\n}}\n</ref>\n\nThis 45-letter word, referred to as \"P45\",<ref name=\"cole89\">Cole, Chris. (1989.) [http://wordways.com/biggest.htm \"The Biggest Hoax\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810033632/http://wordways.com/biggest.htm |date=2014-08-10 }}. ''[[Word Ways: The Journal of Recreational Linguistics]]'', via wordways.com. Retrieved on 2007-10-08.</ref> first appeared in the 1939 supplement to the ''[[Merriam-Webster]] New International Dictionary, Second Edition''.<ref>Miller, Jeff. [http://jeff560.tripod.com/words11.html \"A collection of word oddities and trivia: page 11, long words\"]. (Personal website.) Retrieved on 2007-10-08.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wiktionary pipe|pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis|pneumono\u2026}}\n* [[Vog#Health hazards|Health hazards of vog]]\n* [[Longest word in English|Longest words in English]]\n* [[Supercalifragilisticexpialidocious]]\n* [[List of long place names]]\n* [[Coalworker's pneumoconiosis]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:English words]]\n[[Category:Long words]]\n[[Category:Volcanism]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{short description|Longest word in the English language published in a dictionary}}\n{{About|the term used to describe a form of occupational lung disease|the article about the disease itself|Silicosis}}\n'''''Pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis''''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-us-pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis.ogg|\u02cc|nj|u\u02d0|m|\u0259|n|o\u028a|\u02cc|\u028c|l|t|r|\u0259|\u02cc|m|a\u026a|k|r|\u0259|\u02c8|s|k|\u0252|p|\u026a|k|\u02cc|s|\u026a|l|\u026a|k|o\u028a|v|\u0252|l|\u02cc|k|e\u026a|n|o\u028a|\u02cc|k|o\u028a|n|i|\u02c8|o\u028a|s|\u026a|s}}{{refn|{{OxfordDictionaries.com|accessdate=2017-10-10|Pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis}}}}{{refn|{{MerriamWebsterDictionary|Pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis}}}}) is a word coined by the president of the [[National Puzzlers' League]] as a [[synonym]] for the disease known as [[silicosis]]. It is the [[longest word in the English language]] published in a dictionary, the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', which defines it as \"an artificial long word said to mean a lung disease caused by inhaling very fine ash and sand dust\".<ref>{{cite web |work=Oxford Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |url=http://oxforddictionaries.com/view/entry/m_en_gb0642240#m_en_gb0642240 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719114141/http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis |archivedate=2012-07-19 |title=Definition of {{shy|pneumono|ultra|microscopic|silico|volcano|coniosis}} in Oxford dictionary (British and World English) }}</ref>\n\nSilicosis is a form of occupational lung disease caused by inhalation of crystalline silica dust, and is marked by inflammation and scarring in the form of nodular lesions in the upper lobes of the lungs. It is a type of [[pneumoconiosis]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThis word was invented in the annual meeting of the [[National Puzzlers' League]] (N.P.L.) by its president Everett M. Smith. The word featured in the headline for an article published by the ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]'' on February 23, 1935, titled \"Puzzlers Open 103rd Session Here by Recognizing 45-Letter Word\":\n\n<blockquote>{{shy|Pneumono|ultra|microscopic|silico|volcano|coniosis}} succeeded electrophotomicrographically as the longest word in the English language recognized by the National Puzzlers' League at the opening session of the organization's 103rd semi-annual meeting held yesterday at the Hotel New Yorker. The puzzlers explained that the forty-five-letter word is the synonym of a special form of [[pneumoconiosis]] caused by ultra-microscopic particles of silica [[Volcanic ash|volcanic dust]]...</blockquote>\n\nSubsequently, the word was used in a puzzle book, ''Bedside Manna'', after which time, members of the N.P.L. campaigned to include the word in major dictionaries.<ref>\n{{cite book\n | last = Cole\n | first = Chris\n | title = Wordplay, A Curious Dictionary of Language Oddities\n | publisher = Sterling Publishing Co., Inc.\n | year = 1999\n | pages = 106\u2013107\n | isbn = 0-8069-1797-0\n}}\n</ref>\n\nThis 45-letter word, referred to as \"P45\",<ref name=\"cole89\">Cole, Chris. (1989.) [http://wordways.com/biggest.htm \"The Biggest Hoax\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810033632/http://wordways.com/biggest.htm |date=2014-08-10 }}. ''[[Word Ways: The Journal of Recreational Linguistics]]'', via wordways.com. Retrieved on 2007-10-08.</ref> first appeared in the 1939 supplement to the ''[[Merriam-Webster]] New International Dictionary, Second Edition''.<ref>Miller, Jeff. [http://jeff560.tripod.com/words11.html \"A collection of word oddities and trivia: page 11, long words\"]. (Personal website.) Retrieved on 2007-10-08.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wiktionary pipe|pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis|pneumono\u2026}}\n* [[Vog#Health hazards|Health hazards of vog]]\n* [[Longest word in English|Longest words in English]]\n* [[Supercalifragilisticexpialidocious]]\n* [[List of long place names]]\n* [[Coalworker's pneumoconiosis]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:English words]]\n[[Category:Long words]]\n[[Category:Volcanism]]\n", "name_user": "82.26.12.166", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added context)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pneumonoultramicroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis"}
{"title_page": "Attorney General for Quebec v. Queen Insurance Company", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox court case\n|name               = Attorney General for Quebec v Queen Insurance Company\n|court              =[[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]]\n|image              = British North America Act, 1867.jpg\n|caption            = The ''Queen Insurance Company'' case was an early decision of the Judicial Committee interpreting the ''British North America Act, 1867''\n|full name          = The Honourable Auguste-R\u00e9al Angers, Attorney General for the Province of Quebec, pro Domin\u00e0 Regin\u00e0 v. The Queen Insurance Company\n|date decided       = July 5, 1878\n|citations          = (1878), 3 AC 1090 (PC), [https://www.bailii.org/uk/cases/UKPC/1878/1878_33.html [1878<nowiki>]</nowiki> UKPC 33], [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/116/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 117], [https://archive.org/details/cihm_90129/page/n341/mode/2up 22 LC Jurist 311]\n|judges             = [[James William Colvile|Sir James W. Colvile]] <br>[[Barnes Peacock|Sir Barnes Peacock]] <br/>[[Montague Edward Smith|Sir Montague Smith]] <br>[[Robert P Collier|Sir Robert P. Collier]] <br>[[George Jessel (jurist)|Sir George Jessel]], [[Master of the Rolls]]\n|number of judges   = 5\n|decision by        = \n|prior actions      = ''Attorney General of Quebec pro Domina Regina v Queen Insurance Company'', (1877),  [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/152/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 153], [https://archive.org/details/cihm_90128/page/n95/mode/2up 21 LC Jurist 77] (QC SC); upheld on appeal (1877), [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/130/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 131], 16 CLJ 198, [https://archive.org/details/cihm_90129/page/n337/mode/2up 22 LC Jurist 307] (QC QB).\n|appealed from      = Quebec Court of Queen's Bench [[Image:Maple Leaf (from roundel).svg|20x20px]]\n|opinions           = Provincial licensing fee on insurance companies held unconstitutional under the division of powers\n|keywords           = Provincial taxation and licensing powers\n|italic title       = Yes\n}}\n'''''Attorney General for Quebec v. Queen Insurance Company''''' is a [[Canadian constitutional law]] decision dealing with the taxation and licensing powers of the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|provinces]] under the [[Canadian federalism|federal-provincial division of powers]].\n\nThe case concerned a Quebec statute which imposed a licence fee on insurance companies.  The issue was whether the fee exceeded provincial authority under the ''British North America Act, 1867'' (now known as the ''[[Constitution Act, 1867]]''). The [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]] in Britain, at that time the [[court of last resort]] for [[Canada]] within the [[British Empire]], held that the statute was unconstitutional.\n\nThis was the first case where the Judicial Committee considered the scope of provincial taxation powers and licensing powers under the ''Constitution Act, 1867''.  It was also the first case where the Judicial Committee held that a provincial statute was unconstitutional under the division of powers.\n\n== Facts ==\n\nIn 1875, the [[Quebec Legislature|Legislature of Quebec]] enacted a statute which required every insurance company carrying on business in Quebec to take out a licence.<ref>''An Act to compel Assurers to take out a License'',  SQ 1867 (39 Vict.), c. 7.</ref>  The licence fee was calculated as a percentage of the amounts insured by the insurance policies the company issued.  The insurance company was to pay the fee by means of stamps purchased from the provincial government, which the insurance company was to attach to each insurance policy it issued.  An insurance company which did not attach the necessary stamps to a policy was subject to a fine of $50 for each failure to do so.<ref>''An Act to compel Assurers to take out a License'', ss. 1, 2, and 5.</ref>\n\nThe Queen Insurance Company was an insurance company doing business in Montreal.  It did not take out the licence required by the provincial legislation, and issued three insurance policies without paying the licensing fee.  The Attorney General for Quebec brought an action in the [[Superior Court of Quebec]] to recover the $50 penalty for each policy, for a total of $150.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v. Queen Insurance Company'' (1878), 3 AC 1090, at 1092-1093, [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/116/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 117], at pp. 120-121.</ref>\n\n== Decisions of the Quebec Courts ==\n===Decision of the Superior Court===\n\nAt trial, the insurance company challenged the constitutional validity of the licence fee.  It argued that the legislation exceeded the provincial taxing power set out in section 92(2) of the ''[[Constitution Act, 1867]]'' (formerly the ''British North America Act, 1867''), as well as the provincial licensing power set out in s. 92(9).<ref>''[https://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/Const/section-92.html#h-19 Constitution Act, 1867]'', 30 & 31 Victoria, c. 3. (UK); RSC 1985, App. II, No. 11, s. 92.</ref>\n\nThe insurance company also argued that the provincial law conflicted with a federal act regulating insurance companies.  The company had complied with the federal legislation regulating insurance companies, and had paid a federal licensing charge of $150,000 under the federal law.<ref>''An Act respecting Insurance Companies'', SC 1868, c. 48.</ref>  It argued that the licence under the federal statute gave it the right to carry on the business of insurance, without paying a provincial licensing charge.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v. Queen Insurance Company'' (JCPC), p. 1093 (AC), p. 121 (Cart).</ref>\n\nThe insurance company was successful in the Superior Court.  Justice Torrance held that the law was an indirect tax and therefore not authorised by s. 92(2) of the ''Constitution Act, 1867''.  Relying in part on American federalism precedents, he also held that the licensing provisions intruded on federal jurisdiction.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec pro Domina Regina v. Queen Insurance Co.'' (1877), [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/152/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 153], [https://archive.org/details/cihm_90128/page/n95/mode/2up 21 LC Jurist 77] (QC SC).</ref>\n\nThe Attorney General was represented at trial by [[Edward Carter (politician)|Edward Carter, QC, MP]] and [[Alexandre Lacoste|Alexander Lacoste, QC]].  The Queen Insurance Company was represented by [[John Abbott]], QC (future Prime Minister of Canada), and [[Joseph Doutre]], QC.\n\n===Decision of the Court of Queen's Bench===\n[[File:AntoineAimeDorion23.jpg|thumb|left|[[Antoine-Aim\u00e9 Dorion|Chief Justice Dorion]], one of the judges who held the Act was unconstitutional]]\n\nThe Attorney General appealed to the highest court in Quebec, the [[Quebec Court of Appeal|Quebec Court of Queen's Bench (Appeal Side)]].  By a 4-1 decision, the Queen's Bench agreed with the decision of the Superior Court and dismissed the appeal.<ref>''Attorney General of Quebec v. Queen Insurance Co.'' (1877), [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/130/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 131], 16 C.L.J. 198, [https://archive.org/details/cihm_90129/page/n337/mode/2up 22 LC Jurist 307] (QC QB).</ref>\n\nAll of the judges agreed that the stamp fee was an indirect tax, and therefore could not be supported under the provincial taxation power, given by s. 92(2) of the ''Constitution Act, 1867''.<ref>''Attorney General of Quebec v Queen Insurance Co.'' (QC QB), at pp. 133, 138, 151 (Cart).</ref>\n\nHowever, they disagreed on whether the stamp duty could be upheld as a licence fee.  Four of the judges ([[Antoine-Aim\u00e9 Dorion|Chief Justice Dorion]] and Justices Taschereau, Monk and Tessier) agreed that the duty was not truly a licence fee, but simply a way to impose an indirect tax that was not within provincial authority under s. 92(9). The licence fee was therefore unconstitutional.\n<ref>''Attorney General of Quebec v Queen Insurance Co.'' (QC QB), at pp. 147, 151, and 153 (Cart)</ref> In dissent, Justice Ramsay would have held that the fee was a valid licence fee and therefore the statute could have been upheld on that basis.<ref>''Attorney General of Quebec v Queen Insurance Co.'' (QC QB), at p. 135 (Cart).</ref>\n\nJustice Taschereau was the only one to address the issue of federal jurisdiction.  As part of his analysis of the provincial power to issue licence fees under s. 92(9), he held that insurance companies were subject to federal regulation under the federal jurisdiction over trade and commerce.<ref>''Constitution Act, 1867'', s. 91(2).</ref> and therefore the province could not impose an additional licence on insurance companies doing business in the province.<ref>''Attorney General of Quebec v Queen Insurance Co.'' (QC QB), at pp. 147-148 (Cart).</ref>\n\n== Decision of the Judicial Committee ==\n\n[[File:Sir George Jessel.jpg|thumb|left|[[George Jessel (jurist)|Sir George Jessel]], [[Master of the Rolls]], who wrote the decision that the Act was unconstitutional]]\n\nThe Attorney General for Quebec then appealed the case to the [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]] in Britain, the [[court of last resort]] for [[Canada]] within the [[British Empire]].  (At that time, appeals could go to the Judicial Committee directly from the provincial courts, bypassing the [[Supreme Court of Canada]].)  [[Judah P. Benjamin|Judah P. Benjamin, QC]] and [[John Rigby (politician)|John Rigby]] were counsel for the Attorney General, while the insurance company was represented by Mr Kay, QC and R.W. Gibbs.\n\nThe Judicial Committee dismissed the appeal from the bench, without calling on counsel for the insurance company.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v Queen Insurance Company'' (JCPC), at p. 1096 (AC), p. 1 (UKPC), p. 125 (Cart).</ref>   [[George Jessel (jurist)|Sir George Jessell]], [[Master of the Rolls]], gave the decision for the Committee. He agreed with the Quebec courts that the province did not have the power to impose the fee.  Reviewing the Act, he concluded that it was not really a licensing act at all, as there was no penalty for not taking out a licence, and no prohibition on carrying on business without a licence. The policies issued by an unlicensed insurance company were valid, provided they had a stamp on them.  He concluded that the only purpose of the Act was to raise a revenue.  The province therefore could not rely on s. 92(9) of the ''Constitution Act, 1867'' in support of the Act.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v Queen Insurance Company'' (JCPC), at p. 1099 (AC), p. 4 (UKPC), p. 129 (Cart).</ref>\n\nThe sole question was whether the fee under the Act was direct or indirect taxation.  Jessel concluded that there was ample authority to conclude that a stamp fee of this type was a form of indirect taxation.  It was therefore beyond the provincial power to enact, and the Act was unconstitutional.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v Queen Insurance Company'' (JCPC), at pp. 1101-1102 (AC), pp. 5-6 (UKPC), pp. 129-131 (Cart).</ref>\n\nSince the case could be decided on the basis that the Act exceeded provincial jurisdiction, the Committee did not need to consider the interplay between provincial powers under s. 92 and federal powers under s. 91 of the ''Constitution Act, 1867''.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v Queen Insurance Company'' (JCPC), at p. 10967 (AC), p. 2 (UKPC), pp. 125-126 (Cart).</ref>\n\n== Significance of the decision ==\n\nThis was the first case where the Judicial Committee considered the scope of provincial taxation powers under s. 92(2), and provincial licensing powers under s. 92(9).  It was also the first case where the Judicial Committee held that a provincial statute was unconstitutional under the division of powers.\n\nThe decision has been regularly cited approvingly by the courts since it was made.  The most recent reference to it in the Supreme Court of Canada was in ''Ontario Home Builders' Assn. v. York Region Board of Education''.<ref>''Ontario Home Builders' Assn. v. York Region Board of Education'', [1996] 2 S.C.R. 929.</ref>  Academic commentators have also referred to the decision.<ref>[[G\u00e9rard La Forest|G.V. La Forest]], ''The Allocation of Taxing Power under the Canadian Constitution''.</ref>\n\nThe federal Department of Justice included this decision in the three volume collection of constitutional decisions of the Judicial Committee which the Department published when appeals to the Judicial Committee were abolished.<ref>Richard A. Olmsted, Q.C. (ed.), ''Decisions of the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council relating to the British North America Act, 1867 and the Canadian Constitution, 1867-1954'', vol. I, p. 19 (Ottawa:  Queen's Printer and Controller of Stationery, 1954).</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Attorney General for Quebec}}\n[[Category:Canadian constitutional case law]]\n[[Category:Canadian federalism case law]]\n[[Category:Judicial Committee of the Privy Council cases on appeal from Canada]]\n[[Category:1878 in Canadian case law]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox court case\n|name               = Attorney General for Quebec v Queen Insurance Company\n|court              =[[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]]\n|image              = British North America Act, 1867.jpg\n|caption            = The ''Queen Insurance Company'' case was an early decision of the Judicial Committee interpreting the ''British North America Act, 1867''\n|full name          = The Honourable Auguste-R\u00e9al Angers, Attorney General for the Province of Quebec, pro Domin\u00e0 Regin\u00e0 v. The Queen Insurance Company\n|date decided       = July 5, 1878\n|citations          = (1878), 3 AC 1090 (PC), [https://www.bailii.org/uk/cases/UKPC/1878/1878_33.html [1878<nowiki>]</nowiki> UKPC 33], [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/116/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 117], [https://archive.org/details/cihm_90129/page/n341/mode/2up 22 LC Jurist 311]\n|judges             = [[James William Colvile|Sir James W. Colvile]] <br>[[Barnes Peacock|Sir Barnes Peacock]] <br/>[[Montague Edward Smith|Sir Montague Smith]] <br>[[Robert P Collier|Sir Robert P. Collier]] <br>[[George Jessel (jurist)|Sir George Jessel]], [[Master of the Rolls]]\n|number of judges   = 5\n|decision by        = \n|prior actions      = ''Attorney General of Quebec pro Domina Regina v Queen Insurance Company'', (1877),  [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/152/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 153], [https://archive.org/details/cihm_90128/page/n95/mode/2up 21 LC Jurist 77] (QC SC); upheld on appeal (1877), [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/130/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 131], 16 CLJ 198, [https://archive.org/details/cihm_90129/page/n337/mode/2up 22 LC Jurist 307] (QC QB).\n|appealed from      = Quebec Court of Queen's Bench [[Image:Maple Leaf (from roundel).svg|20x20px]]\n|opinions           = Provincial licensing fee on insurance companies held unconstitutional under the division of powers\n|keywords           = Provincial taxation and licensing powers\n|italic title       = Yes\n}}\n'''''Attorney General for Quebec v. Queen Insurance Company''''' is a [[Canadian constitutional law]] decision dealing with the taxation and licensing powers of the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|provinces]] under the [[Canadian federalism|federal-provincial division of powers]].\n\nThe case concerned a Quebec statute which imposed a licence fee on insurance companies.  The issue was whether the fee exceeded provincial authority under the ''British North America Act, 1867'' (now known as the ''[[Constitution Act, 1867]]''). The [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]] in Britain, at that time the [[court of last resort]] for [[Canada]] within the [[British Empire]], held that the statute was unconstitutional.\n\nThis was the first case where the Judicial Committee considered the scope of provincial taxation powers and licensing powers under the ''Constitution Act, 1867''.  It was also the first case where the Judicial Committee held that a provincial statute was unconstitutional under the division of powers.\n\n== Facts ==\n\nIn 1875, the [[Quebec Legislature|Legislature of Quebec]] enacted a statute which required every insurance company carrying on business in Quebec to take out a licence.<ref>''An Act to compel Assurers to take out a License'',  SQ 1867 (39 Vict.), c. 7.</ref>  The licence fee was calculated as a percentage of the amounts insured by the insurance policies the company issued.  The insurance company was to pay the fee by means of stamps purchased from the provincial government, which the insurance company was to attach to each insurance policy it issued.  An insurance company which did not attach the necessary stamps to a policy was subject to a fine of $50 for each failure to do so.<ref>''An Act to compel Assurers to take out a License'', ss. 1, 2, and 5.</ref>\n\nThe Queen Insurance Company was an insurance company doing business in Montreal.  It did not take out the licence required by the provincial legislation, and issued three insurance policies without paying the licensing fee.  The Attorney General for Quebec brought an action in the [[Superior Court of Quebec]] to recover the $50 penalty for each policy, for a total of $150.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v. Queen Insurance Company'' (1878), 3 AC 1090, at 1092-1093, [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/116/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 117], at pp. 120-121.</ref>\n\n== Decisions of the Quebec Courts ==\n===Decision of the Superior Court===  \n\nAt trial, the insurance company challenged the constitutional validity of the licence fee.  It argued that the legislation exceeded the provincial taxing power set out in section 92(2) of the ''[[Constitution Act, 1867]]'' (formerly the ''British North America Act, 1867''), as well as the provincial licensing power set out in s. 92(9).<ref>''[https://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/Const/section-92.html#h-19 Constitution Act, 1867]'', 30 & 31 Victoria, c. 3. (UK); RSC 1985, App. II, No. 11, s. 92.</ref>\n\nThe insurance company also argued that the provincial law conflicted with a federal act regulating insurance companies.  The company had complied with the federal legislation regulating insurance companies, and had paid a federal licensing charge of $150,000 under the federal law.<ref>''An Act respecting Insurance Companies'', SC 1868, c. 48.</ref>  It argued that the licence under the federal statute gave it the right to carry on the business of insurance, without paying a provincial licensing charge.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v. Queen Insurance Company'' (JCPC), p. 1093 (AC), p. 121 (Cart).</ref>\n\nThe insurance company was successful in the Superior Court.  Justice Torrance held that the law was an indirect tax and therefore not authorised by s. 92(2) of the ''Constitution Act, 1867''.  Relying in part on American federalism precedents, he also held that the licensing provisions intruded on federal jurisdiction.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec pro Domina Regina v. Queen Insurance Co.'' (1877), [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/152/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 153], [https://archive.org/details/cihm_90128/page/n95/mode/2up 21 LC Jurist 77] (QC SC).</ref>\n\nThe Attorney General was represented at trial by [[Edward Carter (politician)|Edward Carter, QC, MP]] and [[Alexandre Lacoste|Alexander Lacoste, QC]].  The Queen Insurance Company was represented by [[John Abbott]], QC (future Prime Minister of Canada), and [[Joseph Doutre]], QC.\n\n===Decision of the Court of Queen's Bench===\n[[File:AntoineAimeDorion23.jpg|thumb|left|[[Antoine-Aim\u00e9 Dorion|Chief Justice Dorion]], one of the judges who held the Act was unconstitutional]]\n\nThe Attorney General appealed to the highest court in Quebec, the [[Quebec Court of Appeal|Quebec Court of Queen's Bench (Appeal Side)]].  By a 4-1 decision, the Queen's Bench agreed with the decision of the Superior Court and dismissed the appeal.<ref>''Attorney General of Quebec v. Queen Insurance Co.'' (1877), [https://archive.org/details/casesdecidedonbr01cartuoft/page/130/mode/2up 1 Cart BNA 131], 16 C.L.J. 198, [https://archive.org/details/cihm_90129/page/n337/mode/2up 22 LC Jurist 307] (QC QB).</ref>\n\nAll of the judges agreed that the stamp fee was an indirect tax, and therefore could not be supported under the provincial taxation power, given by s. 92(2) of the ''Constitution Act, 1867''.<ref>''Attorney General of Quebec v Queen Insurance Co.'' (QC QB), at pp. 133, 138, 151 (Cart).</ref>\n\nHowever, they disagreed on whether the stamp duty could be upheld as a licence fee.  Four of the judges ([[Antoine-Aim\u00e9 Dorion|Chief Justice Dorion]] and Justices Taschereau, Monk and Tessier) agreed that the duty was not truly a licence fee, but simply a way to impose an indirect tax that was not within provincial authority under s. 92(9). The licence fee was therefore unconstitutional.\n<ref>''Attorney General of Quebec v Queen Insurance Co.'' (QC QB), at pp. 147, 151, and 153 (Cart)</ref> In dissent, Justice Ramsay would have held that the fee was a valid licence fee and therefore the statute could have been upheld on that basis.<ref>''Attorney General of Quebec v Queen Insurance Co.'' (QC QB), at p. 135 (Cart).</ref>\n\nJustice Taschereau was the only one to address the issue of federal jurisdiction.  As part of his analysis of the provincial power to issue licence fees under s. 92(9), he held that insurance companies were subject to federal regulation under the federal jurisdiction over trade and commerce.<ref>''Constitution Act, 1867'', s. 91(2).</ref> and therefore the province could not impose an additional licence on insurance companies doing business in the province.<ref>''Attorney General of Quebec v Queen Insurance Co.'' (QC QB), at pp. 147-148 (Cart).</ref>\n\n== Decision of the Judicial Committee ==\n\n[[File:Sir George Jessel.jpg|thumb|left|[[George Jessel (jurist)|Sir George Jessel]], [[Master of the Rolls]], who wrote the decision that the Act was unconstitutional]]\n\nThe Attorney General for Quebec then appealed the case to the [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]] in Britain, the [[court of last resort]] for [[Canada]] within the [[British Empire]].  (At that time, appeals could go to the Judicial Committee directly from the provincial courts, bypassing the [[Supreme Court of Canada]].)  [[Judah P. Benjamin|Judah P. Benjamin, QC]] and [[John Rigby (politician)|John Rigby]] were counsel for the Attorney General, while the insurance company was represented by Mr Kay, QC and R.W. Gibbs.\n\nThe Judicial Committee dismissed the appeal from the bench, without calling on counsel for the insurance company.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v Queen Insurance Company'' (JCPC), at p. 1096 (AC), p. 1 (UKPC), p. 125 (Cart).</ref>   [[George Jessel (jurist)|Sir George Jessell]], [[Master of the Rolls]], gave the decison for the Committee. He agreed with the Quebec courts that the province did not have the power to impose the fee.  Reviewing the Act, he concluded that it was not really a licensing act at all, as there was no penalty for not taking out a licence, and no prohibition on carrying on business without a licence. The policies issued by an unlicensed insurance company were valid, provided they had a stamp on them.  He concluded that the only purpose of the Act was to raise a revenue.  The province therefore could not rely on s. 92(9) of the ''Constitution Act, 1867'' in support of the Act.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v Queen Insurance Company'' (JCPC), at p. 1099 (AC), p. 4 (UKPC), p. 129 (Cart).</ref> \n\nThe sole question was whether the fee under the Act was direct or indirect taxation.  Jessel concluded that there was ample authority to conclude that a stamp fee of this type was a form of indirect taxation.  It was therefore beyond the provincial power to enact, and the Act was unconstitutional.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v Queen Insurance Company'' (JCPC), at pp. 1101-1102 (AC), pp. 5-6 (UKPC), pp. 129-131 (Cart).</ref>\n\nSince the case could be decided on the basis that the Act exeeded provincial jurisdiction, the Committee did not need to consider the interplay betwen provincial powers under s. 92 and federal powers under s. 91 of the ''Constitution Act, 1867''.<ref>''Attorney General for Quebec v Queen Insurance Company'' (JCPC), at p. 10967 (AC), p. 2 (UKPC), pp. 125-126 (Cart).</ref>\n\n== Significance of the decision ==\n\nThis was the first case where the Judicial Committee considered the scope of provincial taxation powers under s. 92(2), and provincial licensing powers under s. 92(9).  It was also the first case where the Judicial Committee held that a provincial statute was unconstitutional under the division of powers.\n\nThe decision has been regularly cited approvingly by the courts since it was made.  The most recent reference to it in the Supreme Court of Canada was in ''Ontario Home Builders' Assn. v. York Region Board of Education''.<ref>''Ontario Home Builders' Assn. v. York Region Board of Education'', [1996] 2 S.C.R. 929.</ref>  Academic commentators have also referred to the decision.<ref>[[G\u00e9rard La Forest|G.V. La Forest]], ''The Allocation of Taxing Power under the Canadian Constitution''.</ref>\n\nThe federal Department of Justice included this decision in the three volume collection of constitutional decisions of the Judicial Committee which the Department published when appeals to the Judicial Committee were abolished.<ref>Richard A. Olmsted, Q.C. (ed.), ''Decisions of the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council relating to the British North America Act, 1867 and the Canadian Constitution, 1867-1954'', vol. I, p. 19 (Ottawa:  Queen's Printer and Controller of Stationery, 1954).</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Attorney General for Quebec}}\n[[Category:Canadian constitutional case law]]\n[[Category:Canadian federalism case law]]\n[[Category:Judicial Committee of the Privy Council cases on appeal from Canada]]\n[[Category:1878 in Canadian case law]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: betwen \u2192 between, decison \u2192 decision, exeeded \u2192 exceeded", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attorney_General_for_Quebec_v._Queen_Insurance_Company"}
{"title_page": "Elisabeth Bik", "text_new": "{{short description|Dutch microbiologist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Elisabeth Bik\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = Square Headshot Elisabeth Bik.png\n| image_size        = \n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date        = {{birth year and age |1966}}\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| home_town         =\n| other_names       = \n| siglum            =\n| pronounce         =\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = \n| workplaces        = {{ublist|[[Stanford University]]|[[uBiome]]}}\n| patrons           = \n| education         = \n| alma_mater        = [[Utrecht University]]\n| thesis_title      = Cholera: vaccine development and evolution of epidemic ''Vibrio cholerae'' strains\n| thesis_url        = <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year       = 1996\n| doctoral_advisor  = <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner           = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children          = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Elisabeth Margaretha Harbers-Bik''' (born 1966) is a microbiologist and scientific integrity consultant.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2019-11-19|title=The science institutions hiring integrity inspectors to vet their papers|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-03529-w|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=575|pages=430\u2013433|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-03529-w}}</ref> Bik has gained widespread recognition for detecting [[Scientific misconduct#Photo manipulation|photo manipulation]] in scientific publications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lastwordonnothing.com/2019/02/12/the-western-blot-vigilante/|title=The Last Word On Nothing {{!}} The Fraud Finder: A conversation with Elisabeth Bik|website=www.lastwordonnothing.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>{{better source needed}} Bik is the founder of Microbiome Digest,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://microbiomedigest.com/|title=Microbiome Digest|website=MicrobiomeDigest.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> a blog with daily updates on [[microbiome]] research, and the Science Integrity Digest blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scienceintegritydigest.com/ |title=Science Integrity Digest |website=ScienceIntegrityDigest.com|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Maddox Prize 2019 |url=https://senseaboutscience.org/activities/maddox-prize-2019/ |website=senseaboutscience.org |publisher=Sense about Science |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBik was born in the [[Netherlands]]. She attended [[Utrecht University]] majoring in biology, and continued there for her doctorate. Her dissertation was about developing vaccines for new classes of ''[[Vibrio cholerae]]'' involved in [[cholera]] epidemics across India and Bangladesh.<ref name=dissertation>{{cite book |last1=Bik |first1=Elisabeth M |title=Cholera: vaccine development and evolution of epidemic Vibrio cholerae strains |date=1996 |publisher=Utrecht University |isbn=90-90091-73-4 |url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?cluster=7401088272344486802&hl=en&as_sdt=2005&sciodt=0,5 |format=Dissertation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bik|first=Elisabeth M.|last2=Mooi|first2=Frits R.|date=1997-04-01|title=The evolution of epidemic Vibrio cholerae strains|url=https://www.cell.com/trends/microbiology/abstract/S0966-842X(96)10086-X|journal=Trends in Microbiology|language=English|volume=5|issue=4|pages=161\u2013165|doi=10.1016/S0966-842X(96)10086-X|issn=0966-842X|pmid=9141191}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mooi|first=F. R.|last2=Gouw|first2=R. D.|last3=Bunschoten|first3=A. E.|last4=Bik|first4=E. M.|date=1995-01-01|title=Genesis of the novel epidemic Vibrio cholerae O139 strain: evidence for horizontal transfer of genes involved in polysaccharide synthesis.|journal=The EMBO Journal|volume=14|issue=2|pages=209\u2013216|doi=10.1002/j.1460-2075.1995.tb06993.x|issn=1460-2075}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/eye-for-manipulation--a-profile-of-elisabeth-bik-65839|title=Eye for Manipulation: A Profile of Elisabeth Bik|website=The Scientist Magazine\u00ae|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> Her doctorate and postdoctoral studies were conducted at the molecular microbiology department in the National Institute of Health and the Environment in [[Bilthoven]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bik |first1=Elisabeth |title=Elisabeth Bik - Consultant - Harbers Bik LLC |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/elisabeth-bik-4376782/ |website=www.linkedin.com |publisher=LinkedIn |accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career  ==\n=== Public sector ===\n\nAfter receiving her Ph.D., Bik worked for the [[Netherlands National Institute for Public Health and the Environment]] and St. Antonius Hospital in [[Nieuwegein]], where she organized the development of new molecular techniques for identifying infectious agents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://microbiomedigest.com/sample-page/in-the-news/|title=Elisabeth Bik|date=2016-04-28|website=Microbiome Digest - Bik's Picks|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peerj.com/ElisabethBik/|title=Profile - Elisabeth Bik|website=peerj.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Academia ===\n\nIn 2001, Bik moved to California to work at [[Stanford University]] in the laboratory of [[David Relman]], where her work focused on human microbiomes, previously unidentified species in them, and their diversity across individuals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Relman|first=David A.|last2=Nelson|first2=Karen E.|last3=Gill|first3=Steven R.|last4=Sargent|first4=Michael|last5=Dethlefsen|first5=Les|last6=Purdom|first6=Elizabeth|last7=Bernstein|first7=Charles N.|last8=Bik|first8=Elisabeth M.|last9=Eckburg|first9=Paul B.|date=2005-06-10|title=Diversity of the Human Intestinal Microbial Flora|journal=Science|volume=308|issue=5728|pages=1635\u20131638|doi=10.1126/science.1110591|issn=0036-8075|pmid=15831718|pmc=1395357}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Relman|first=David A.|last2=Blaser|first2=Martin J.|last3=Perez-Perez|first3=Guillermo|last4=Francois|first4=Fritz|last5=Purdom|first5=Elizabeth A.|last6=Nelson|first6=Karen E.|last7=Gill|first7=Steven R.|last8=Eckburg|first8=Paul B.|last9=Bik|first9=Elisabeth M.|date=2006-01-17|title=Molecular analysis of the bacterial microbiota in the human stomach|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=103|issue=3|pages=732\u2013737|doi=10.1073/pnas.0506655103|issn=0027-8424|pmid=16407106|pmc=1334644}}</ref> Her work explored other mucosal microbiomes, confirming that the human oral microbiota contains distinct genera from the gut microbiota.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Relman|first=David A.|last2=Fraser-Liggett|first2=Claire M.|last3=Gill|first3=Steven R.|last4=Nelson|first4=Karen E.|last5=Emmanuel F. Mongodin|last6=Emerson|first6=Joanne|last7=Loomer|first7=Peter|last8=Armitage|first8=Gary C.|last9=Long|first9=Clara Davis|date=August 2010|title=Bacterial diversity in the oral cavity of 10 healthy individuals|journal=The ISME Journal|volume=4|issue=8|pages=962\u2013974|doi=10.1038/ismej.2010.30|pmid=20336157|pmc=2941673|issn=1751-7370}}</ref>\n\nWhile at Stanford, Bik worked on an [[Office of Naval Research]] project to study the microbiome of dolphins and sea lions in San Diego. She found that their microbiome was distinct from other mammals, and influenced by the sea they lived in.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bik|first=Elisabeth M.|last2=Costello|first2=Elizabeth K.|last3=Switzer|first3=Alexandra D.|last4=Callahan|first4=Benjamin J.|last5=Holmes|first5=Susan P.|last6=Wells|first6=Randall S.|last7=Carlin|first7=Kevin P.|last8=Jensen|first8=Eric D.|last9=Venn-Watson|first9=Stephanie|last10=Relman|first10=David A.|date=2016-02-03|title=Marine mammals harbor unique microbiotas shaped by and yet distinct from the sea|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=1\u201313|doi=10.1038/ncomms10516|pmid=26839246|issn=2041-1723|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n=== Private sector ===\n\nIn 2016, Bik left Stanford to work for [[uBiome]], a biotech company involved in the sequencing of human microbiomes, before leaving the company in 2018 to work full-time on analyzing scientific papers for image duplication and other malpractices.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Science integrity ===\n\nIn 2014, she started the blog ''Microbiome Digest'', where she provided easy-to-understand commentaries on recent scientific papers.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.editage.com/insights/i-have-found-about-2000-problematic-papers-says-dr-elisabeth-bik|title=I have found about 2,000 problematic papers, says Dr. Elisabeth Bik|date=2019-08-08|website=Editage Insights|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> The blog soon became a success, and Bik enlisted help from her colleagues on Twitter to manage the content.<ref name=\":1\" /> She is also an active contributor to [[Retraction Watch]] and [[PubPeer]], highlighting scientific papers that present falsified, duplicated, and questionable data, such as in [[western blot]] images.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2019/05/07/meet-elisabeth-bik-who-finds-problematic-images-in-scientific-papers-for-free/|title=Meet Elisabeth Bik, who finds problematic images in scientific papers for free|last=Oransky|first=Author Ivan|date=2019-05-07|website=Retraction Watch|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubpeer.com/|title=PubPeer - Search publications and join the conversation.|website=pubpeer.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> \n\nTogether with [[Arturo Casadevall|Arturo Cassadevall]] and [[Ferric Fang]], Bik published an [[mBio]] paper investigating the prevalence of these questionable practices within published scientific papers, where they found nearly 400 papers with intentional figure manipulation (i.e. about 800 duplicate images).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fang|first=Ferric C.|last2=Casadevall|first2=Arturo|last3=Bik|first3=Elisabeth M.|date=2016-07-06|title=The Prevalence of Inappropriate Image Duplication in Biomedical Research Publications|journal=mBio|volume=7|issue=3|pages=e00809\u201316|doi=10.1128/mBio.00809-16|issn=2150-7511|pmid=27273827|pmc=4941872}}</ref> She estimates half of these were created with the intention to mislead. Bik is active on the social media micro-blogging platform, [[Twitter]], where she posts potentially duplicated figures for her more than 60,000 Twitter followers ({{As of|alt=as of April, 2020|2020|April}}) to investigate. Her investigations have exposed significant levels of scientific misconduct in several journals.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2018, Bik was featured on the pop science podcast \"Everything Hertz.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://everythinghertz.com/guests/elisabeth-bik|title=Everything Hertz - Elisabeth Bik|website=everythinghertz.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Bik announced via [[Twitter]] that she was taking a year off paid work to investigate scientific misconduct,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite tweet |user=MicrobiomDigest |author-link=Elisabeth Bik |number=1121796872794820610 |date=April 26, 2019 |title=I am taking a year off from paid work to focus more on my science misconduct volunteer work. Science needs more help to detect image duplication, plagiarism, fabricated results, and predatory publishers.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fotofocus.org/symposium/2019/participants/|title=About the Participants|website=FotoFocus Cincinnati|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> the subject on which she coauthored a [[Preregistration|preregistered test]] suggesting that \"academic culture, peer control, cash-based publication incentives and national misconduct policies,\" but not pressure to publish, may affect scientific integrity, with nationality being a stronger predictor than individual attributes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fanelli |first1=Daniele |last2=Costas |first2=Rodrigo |last3=Fang |first3=Ferric C. |last4=Casadevall |first4=Arturo |last5=Bik |first5=Elisabeth M. |title=Testing Hypotheses on Risk Factors for Scientific Misconduct via Matched-Control Analysis of Papers Containing Problematic Image Duplications |journal=Science and Engineering Ethics |date=1 June 2019 |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=771\u2013789 |doi=10.1007/s11948-018-0023-7 |pmid=29460082 |pmc=6591179 |language=en |issn=1471-5546}}</ref> Her analysis of 960 recent papers published in ''[[Molecular and Cellular Biology]]'' found that 6.1% contained inappropriately duplicated images, about 10% of which were retracted, and led to a pilot image screening program at the journal identifying problems with 14.5% of subsequent submissions.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bik |first1=Elisabeth M. |last2=Fang |first2=Ferric C. |last3=Kullas |first3=Amy L. |last4=Davis |first4=Roger J. |last5=Casadevall |first5=Arturo |title=Analysis and Correction of Inappropriate Image Duplication: the Molecular and Cellular Biology Experience |journal=Molecular and Cellular Biology |date=15 October 2018 |volume=38 |issue=20 |doi=10.1128/MCB.00309-18 |pmid=30037982 |url=https://mcb.asm.org/content/38/20/e00309-18.abstract |accessdate=25 November 2019 |language=en |issn=0270-7306|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Bik identified over 400 research papers published in China over the previous three years, apparently all originating from the same \"paper mill\" company providing full service production of articles describing fake research for medical students on demand. Bik said, \"students in China need to have a paper published to get their MD, but they do not have time to do research, so that is an unrealistic goal.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Basu |first1=Mohana |title=Researchers flag over 400 'dubious papers' published in China in last 3 years |url=https://theprint.in/science/researchers-flag-over-400-dubious-papers-published-in-china-in-last-3-years/370801/ |accessdate=27 February 2020 |work=ThePrint |date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Scholia}}\n* [https://microbiomedigest.com/ Microbiome Digest] blog\n* {{google scholar id|Jo9LMfoAAAAJ}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bik, Elisabeth}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch microbiologists]]\n[[Category:Utrecht University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dutch microbiologist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Elisabeth Bik\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = Square Headshot Elisabeth Bik.png\n| image_size        = \n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date        = {{birth year and age |1966}}\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| home_town         =\n| other_names       = \n| siglum            =\n| pronounce         =\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = \n| workplaces        = {{ublist|[[Stanford University]]|[[uBiome]]}}\n| patrons           = \n| education         = \n| alma_mater        = [[Utrecht University]]\n| thesis_title      = Cholera: vaccine development and evolution of epidemic ''Vibrio cholerae'' strains\n| thesis_url        = <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year       = 1996\n| doctoral_advisor  = <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner           = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children          = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Elisabeth Margaretha Harbers-Bik''' (born 1966) is a microbiologist and scientific integrity consultant.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbott|first=Alison|date=2019-11-19|title=The science institutions hiring integrity inspectors to vet their papers|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-03529-w|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=575|pages=430\u2013433|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-03529-w}}</ref> Bik has gained widespread recognition for detecting [[Scientific misconduct#Photo manipulation|photo manipulation]] in scientific publications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lastwordonnothing.com/2019/02/12/the-western-blot-vigilante/|title=The Last Word On Nothing {{!}} The Fraud Finder: A conversation with Elisabeth Bik|website=www.lastwordonnothing.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>{{better source needed}} Bik is the founder of Microbiome Digest,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://microbiomedigest.com/|title=Microbiome Digest|website=MicrobiomeDigest.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> a blog with daily updates on [[microbiome]] research, and the Science Integrity Digest blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scienceintegritydigest.com/ |title=Science Integrity Digest |website=ScienceIntegrityDigest.com|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Maddox Prize 2019 |url=https://senseaboutscience.org/activities/maddox-prize-2019/ |website=senseaboutscience.org |publisher=Sense about Science |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBik was born in the [[Netherlands]]. She attended [[Utrecht University]] majoring in biology, and continued there for her doctorate. Her dissertation was about developing vaccines for new classes of ''[[Vibrio cholerae]]'' involved in [[cholera]] epidemics across India and Bangladesh.<ref name=dissertation>{{cite book |last1=Bik |first1=Elisabeth M |title=Cholera: vaccine development and evolution of epidemic Vibrio cholerae strains |date=1996 |publisher=Utrecht University |isbn=90-90091-73-4 |url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?cluster=7401088272344486802&hl=en&as_sdt=2005&sciodt=0,5 |format=Dissertation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bik|first=Elisabeth M.|last2=Mooi|first2=Frits R.|date=1997-04-01|title=The evolution of epidemic Vibrio cholerae strains|url=https://www.cell.com/trends/microbiology/abstract/S0966-842X(96)10086-X|journal=Trends in Microbiology|language=English|volume=5|issue=4|pages=161\u2013165|doi=10.1016/S0966-842X(96)10086-X|issn=0966-842X|pmid=9141191}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mooi|first=F. R.|last2=Gouw|first2=R. D.|last3=Bunschoten|first3=A. E.|last4=Bik|first4=E. M.|date=1995-01-01|title=Genesis of the novel epidemic Vibrio cholerae O139 strain: evidence for horizontal transfer of genes involved in polysaccharide synthesis.|journal=The EMBO Journal|volume=14|issue=2|pages=209\u2013216|doi=10.1002/j.1460-2075.1995.tb06993.x|issn=1460-2075}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/eye-for-manipulation--a-profile-of-elisabeth-bik-65839|title=Eye for Manipulation: A Profile of Elisabeth Bik|website=The Scientist Magazine\u00ae|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> Her doctorate and postdoctoral studies were conducted at the molecular microbiology department in the National Institute of Health and the Environment in [[Bilthoven]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bik |first1=Elisabeth |title=Elisabeth Bik - Consultant - Harbers Bik LLC |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/elisabeth-bik-4376782/ |website=www.linkedin.com |publisher=LinkedIn |accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career  ==\n=== Public sector ===\n\nAfter receiving her Ph.D., Bik worked for the [[Netherlands National Institute for Public Health and the Environment]] and St. Antonius Hospital in [[Nieuwegein]], where she organized the development of new molecular techniques for identifying infectious agents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://microbiomedigest.com/sample-page/in-the-news/|title=Elisabeth Bik|date=2016-04-28|website=Microbiome Digest - Bik's Picks|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peerj.com/ElisabethBik/|title=Profile - Elisabeth Bik|website=peerj.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Academia ===\n\nIn 2001, Bik moved to California to work at [[Stanford University]] in the laboratory of [[David Relman]], where her work focused on human microbiomes, previously unidentified species in them, and their diversity across individuals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Relman|first=David A.|last2=Nelson|first2=Karen E.|last3=Gill|first3=Steven R.|last4=Sargent|first4=Michael|last5=Dethlefsen|first5=Les|last6=Purdom|first6=Elizabeth|last7=Bernstein|first7=Charles N.|last8=Bik|first8=Elisabeth M.|last9=Eckburg|first9=Paul B.|date=2005-06-10|title=Diversity of the Human Intestinal Microbial Flora|journal=Science|volume=308|issue=5728|pages=1635\u20131638|doi=10.1126/science.1110591|issn=0036-8075|pmid=15831718|pmc=1395357}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Relman|first=David A.|last2=Blaser|first2=Martin J.|last3=Perez-Perez|first3=Guillermo|last4=Francois|first4=Fritz|last5=Purdom|first5=Elizabeth A.|last6=Nelson|first6=Karen E.|last7=Gill|first7=Steven R.|last8=Eckburg|first8=Paul B.|last9=Bik|first9=Elisabeth M.|date=2006-01-17|title=Molecular analysis of the bacterial microbiota in the human stomach|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=103|issue=3|pages=732\u2013737|doi=10.1073/pnas.0506655103|issn=0027-8424|pmid=16407106|pmc=1334644}}</ref> Her work explored other mucosal microbiomes, confirming that the human oral microbiota contains distinct genera from the gut microbiota.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Relman|first=David A.|last2=Fraser-Liggett|first2=Claire M.|last3=Gill|first3=Steven R.|last4=Nelson|first4=Karen E.|last5=Emmanuel F. Mongodin|last6=Emerson|first6=Joanne|last7=Loomer|first7=Peter|last8=Armitage|first8=Gary C.|last9=Long|first9=Clara Davis|date=August 2010|title=Bacterial diversity in the oral cavity of 10 healthy individuals|journal=The ISME Journal|volume=4|issue=8|pages=962\u2013974|doi=10.1038/ismej.2010.30|pmid=20336157|pmc=2941673|issn=1751-7370}}</ref>\n\nWhile at Stanford, Bik worked on an [[Office of Naval Research]] project to study the microbiome of dolphins and sea lions in San Diego. She found that their microbiome was distinct from other mammals, and influenced by the sea they lived in.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bik|first=Elisabeth M.|last2=Costello|first2=Elizabeth K.|last3=Switzer|first3=Alexandra D.|last4=Callahan|first4=Benjamin J.|last5=Holmes|first5=Susan P.|last6=Wells|first6=Randall S.|last7=Carlin|first7=Kevin P.|last8=Jensen|first8=Eric D.|last9=Venn-Watson|first9=Stephanie|last10=Relman|first10=David A.|date=2016-02-03|title=Marine mammals harbor unique microbiotas shaped by and yet distinct from the sea|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=1\u201313|doi=10.1038/ncomms10516|pmid=26839246|issn=2041-1723|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n=== Private sector ===\n\nIn 2016, Bik left Stanford to work for [[uBiome]], a biotech company involved in the sequencing of human microbiomes, before leaving the company in 2018 to work full-time on analyzing scientific papers for image duplication and other malpractices.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Science integrity ===\n\nIn 2014, she had started the blog ''Microbiome Digest'', where she provided easy-to-understand commentaries on recent scientific papers.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.editage.com/insights/i-have-found-about-2000-problematic-papers-says-dr-elisabeth-bik|title=I have found about 2,000 problematic papers, says Dr. Elisabeth Bik|date=2019-08-08|website=Editage Insights|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> The blog soon became a success, and Bik enlisted help from her colleagues on Twitter to manage the content.<ref name=\":1\" /> She is also an active contributor to [[Retraction Watch]] and [[PubPeer]], highlighting scientific papers that present falsified, duplicated, and questionable data, such as in [[western blot]] images.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2019/05/07/meet-elisabeth-bik-who-finds-problematic-images-in-scientific-papers-for-free/|title=Meet Elisabeth Bik, who finds problematic images in scientific papers for free|last=Oransky|first=Author Ivan|date=2019-05-07|website=Retraction Watch|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubpeer.com/|title=PubPeer - Search publications and join the conversation.|website=pubpeer.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> \n\nTogether with [[Arturo Casadevall|Arturo Cassadevall]] and [[Ferric Fang]], Bik published an [[mBio]] paper investigating the prevalence of these questionable practices within published scientific papers, where they found nearly 400 papers with intentional figure manipulation (i.e. about 800 duplicate images).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fang|first=Ferric C.|last2=Casadevall|first2=Arturo|last3=Bik|first3=Elisabeth M.|date=2016-07-06|title=The Prevalence of Inappropriate Image Duplication in Biomedical Research Publications|journal=mBio|volume=7|issue=3|pages=e00809\u201316|doi=10.1128/mBio.00809-16|issn=2150-7511|pmid=27273827|pmc=4941872}}</ref> She estimates half of these were created with the intention to mislead. Bik is active on the social media micro-blogging platform, [[Twitter]], where she posts potentially duplicated figures for her more than 60,000 Twitter followers ({{As of|alt=as of April, 2020|2020|April}}) to investigate. Her investigations have exposed significant levels of scientific misconduct in several journals.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2018, Bik was featured on the pop science podcast \"Everything Hertz.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://everythinghertz.com/guests/elisabeth-bik|title=Everything Hertz - Elisabeth Bik|website=everythinghertz.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Bik announced via [[Twitter]] that she was taking a year off paid work to investigate scientific misconduct,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite tweet |user=MicrobiomDigest |author-link=Elisabeth Bik |number=1121796872794820610 |date=April 26, 2019 |title=I am taking a year off from paid work to focus more on my science misconduct volunteer work. Science needs more help to detect image duplication, plagiarism, fabricated results, and predatory publishers.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fotofocus.org/symposium/2019/participants/|title=About the Participants|website=FotoFocus Cincinnati|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> the subject on which she coauthored a [[Preregistration|preregistered test]] suggesting that \"academic culture, peer control, cash-based publication incentives and national misconduct policies,\" but not pressure to publish, may affect scientific integrity, with nationality being a stronger predictor than individual attributes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fanelli |first1=Daniele |last2=Costas |first2=Rodrigo |last3=Fang |first3=Ferric C. |last4=Casadevall |first4=Arturo |last5=Bik |first5=Elisabeth M. |title=Testing Hypotheses on Risk Factors for Scientific Misconduct via Matched-Control Analysis of Papers Containing Problematic Image Duplications |journal=Science and Engineering Ethics |date=1 June 2019 |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=771\u2013789 |doi=10.1007/s11948-018-0023-7 |pmid=29460082 |pmc=6591179 |language=en |issn=1471-5546}}</ref> Her analysis of 960 recent papers published in ''[[Molecular and Cellular Biology]]'' found that 6.1% contained inappropriately duplicated images, about 10% of which were retracted, and led to a pilot image screening program at the journal identifying problems with 14.5% of subsequent submissions.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bik |first1=Elisabeth M. |last2=Fang |first2=Ferric C. |last3=Kullas |first3=Amy L. |last4=Davis |first4=Roger J. |last5=Casadevall |first5=Arturo |title=Analysis and Correction of Inappropriate Image Duplication: the Molecular and Cellular Biology Experience |journal=Molecular and Cellular Biology |date=15 October 2018 |volume=38 |issue=20 |doi=10.1128/MCB.00309-18 |pmid=30037982 |url=https://mcb.asm.org/content/38/20/e00309-18.abstract |accessdate=25 November 2019 |language=en |issn=0270-7306|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Bik identified over 400 research papers published in China over the previous three years, apparently all originating from the same \"paper mill\" company providing full service production of articles describing fake research for medical students on demand. Bik said, \"students in China need to have a paper published to get their MD, but they do not have time to do research, so that is an unrealistic goal.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Basu |first1=Mohana |title=Researchers flag over 400 'dubious papers' published in China in last 3 years |url=https://theprint.in/science/researchers-flag-over-400-dubious-papers-published-in-china-in-last-3-years/370801/ |accessdate=27 February 2020 |work=ThePrint |date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Scholia}}\n* [https://microbiomedigest.com/ Microbiome Digest] blog\n* {{google scholar id|Jo9LMfoAAAAJ}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bik, Elisabeth}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch microbiologists]]\n[[Category:Utrecht University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Bueller 007", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eScience integrity", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elisabeth_Bik"}
{"title_page": "Tomb of the Unknown Soldier (Kiev)", "text_new": "[[File:Fallen Heroes Alley in Kiev 24.07.08.JPG|thumb|The tomb in 2008.]]\nThe '''Tomb of the Unknown Soldier''' ({{Lang-uk|\u041c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043e\u043b\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430}}) is a [[war memorial]] located in the [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] capital of [[Kiev]], dedicated to the soldiers of the [[Red Army]] killed in the [[Second World War]]. It is situated at the Memorial of Eternal Glory inside the [[Park of Eternal Glory]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wikimapia.org/24759/Tomb-of-the-Unknown-Soldier|title=Tomb of the Unknown Soldier - Kyiv|website=wikimapia.org}}</ref> The memorial is a 27 meters high obelisk, with an [[eternal flame]] burning at the tomb  The Alley of Heroes leads to the tomb.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kyivmaps.com/en/places/memorial-vicnoi-slavi|title=Monument \"Unkown Soldiers Grave\" - information, events, map, reviews|website=kyivmaps.com}}</ref>\n\nThe tomb was opened on 6 November 1957, on the eve of the [[ruby jubilee]] of the [[October Revolution]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warmuseum.kiev.ua/_ua/martirolog/necropolis/1_park_slavi/|title=\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0439 \u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0457 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u0443 \u0414\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0456\u0439 \u0441\u0432\u0456\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0439 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0456|website=warmuseum.kiev.ua}}</ref> On 8 May 1967, is was dedicated to the memory of all the unknown Ukrainian soldiers who gave their lives in the Liberation of Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/8071/tomb_of_the_unknown_ukrainian_soldier|title=Tomb of the Unknown Ukrainian Soldier - Find A...|website=www.findagrave.com}}</ref> International dignitaries such as U.S. President [[Richard Nixon]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dissolve.com/video/President-Nixon-visits-tomb-unknown-soldier-Kiev-royalty-free-stock-video-footage/001-D378-38-306|title=Clip D378_38_306, from Dissolve|website=Dissolve}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/05/30/archives/greeting-in-kiev-the-negotiating-over-officials-relax-at-farewell.html|title=Greeting in Kiev|first=Robert B. Semple Jr Special to The New York|last=Times|date=May 30, 1972|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Azerbaijani President [[Ilham Aliyev]],<ref>{{cite web |url= https://azertag.az/en/xeber/Azerbaijani_President_visits_Tomb_of_Unknown_Soldier_in_Kiev-598293?__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=ff9c8886b76c6ef5c9a4639e54820a378fc99069-1586712456-0-AZdBCvGkvorRedxWVTLawnyZaV_p4pqGVyiV-5MHMWl945AyyR2l1qoVAgPmE05zhQKEi0ydE54CDO3MU00BoF8j0QiTJKQgQJ_jgDy8-zSnsEfo9KZQboIJXKA-yQlmATDs_K4cYYsqH03tX96D5yg4zijvelR9pkgyD7pBT9Hqvlh7TrpYyl0xq_MR6vmFYc46vwhQO4KWXd4IKN6rvIJHx_Ugup94XBugu2zYQCwg9Emw-SJjTNwbFX7naFQAPbGhgUZ35K3m4DkpmfZ0FaQKt-SNWXs-cNnO2RFZfMN8sz9GojYdok6ca-L2UzovInf2V8cu_QVcdKoQo9-R9QEGYPECjmSX443nlfLeBNZIVSvBTeXscW9HSz-VFySNBg|title=Azerbaijani President visits Tomb of Unknown Soldier in Kiev |last= |first= |date= 28 October 2010|website= azertag.az|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Lithuanian Prime Minister [[Algirdas Butkevi\u010dius]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ministraspirmininkas.lrv.lt/en/gallery/prime-minister-algirdas-butkevicius-paid-a-tribute-to-victims-at-the-memorial-in-commemoration-of-famines-victims-in-ukraine-and-a-tomb-of-the-unknown-soldier-kiev|title=Prime Minister Algirdas Butkevi\u010dius paid a tribute to victims at the Memorial in Commemoration of Famines\u2019 Victims in Ukraine and a Tomb of the Unknown Soldier (Kiev)|website=ministraspirmininkas.lrv.lt}}</ref> Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.by/en/press/news_mfa/afce7f66183638f8.html|title=President of Belarus Takes Part in Celebration of the 60th Anniversary of Liberation of Ukraine - Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Belarus|website=mfa.gov.by|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref> and Turkish Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdogan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/turkey/turkish-pm-visits-tomb-of-unknown-soldier-in-kiev/336215|title=Turkish pm visits Tomb of Unknown Soldier in Kiev|website=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref> have visited and laid wreaths at the tomb. The British government has annually held [[Remembrance Day]] services at the tomb.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/remembrance-day-in-kyiv|title=Remembrance Day in Kyiv|website=GOV.UK}}</ref>\n\nSince [[Ukrainian decommunization laws]] came into effect in 2015, the monument has become a divisive symbol between the pro-Russian population and the nationalist population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://architectuul.com/architecture/the-memorial-park-of-eternal-glory|title=The Memorial Park of Eternal Glory|website=architectuul.com}}</ref> In August 2016, neo-Nazis destroyed the memorial on the grave of the unknown soldier. On 7 November 2017 which was the day after the monument's 60th anniversary, vandals filled the eternal flame with wet cement, thus ceasing the flame for the first time since its inception. The flame was later re-lit by authorities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stalkerzone.org/vandals-cemented-eternal-flame-memorial-tomb-unknown-soldier-kiev/|title=Vandals Cemented the Eternal Flame of the Memorial at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier in Kiev \u2022 Stalker Zone|date=November 8, 2017|website=Stalker Zone}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Kiev's unknown soldier.jpg|The unknown soldier\nFile:80-382-0519 Kiev Slavy Komplex 004.jpg|A [[Ukrainian Navy]] [[honor guard]] marching to the tomb.\nFile:Eternal flame in Kiev.JPG|The eternal flame\nFile:Dmitry Medvedev in Ukraine 17 May 2010-3.jpeg|[[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[Viktor Yanukovich]] at the tomb.\nFile:\u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438 \u043f\u043b..jpg|The eternal flame at night.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier (Moscow)]]\n*[[Victory Square (Minsk)]]\n*[[Eternity Memorial Complex, Chi\u0219in\u0103u]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Soviet military memorials and cemeteries]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials built in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1957]]\n[[Category:Tombs of Unknown Soldiers]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Ukraine]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Fallen Heroes Alley in Kiev 24.07.08.JPG|thumb|The tomb in 2008.]]\nThe '''Tomb of the Unknown Soldier''' ({{Lang-uk|\u041c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043e\u043b\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430}}) is a [[war memorial]] located in the [[Ukraine|Ukranian]] capital of [[Kiev]], dedicated to the soldiers of the [[Red Army]] killed in the [[Second World War]]. It is situated at the Memorial of Eternal Glory inside the [[Park of Eternal Glory]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wikimapia.org/24759/Tomb-of-the-Unknown-Soldier|title=Tomb of the Unknown Soldier - Kyiv|website=wikimapia.org}}</ref> The memorial is a 27 meters high obelisk, with an [[eternal flame]] burning at the tomb  The Alley of Heroes leads to the tomb.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kyivmaps.com/en/places/memorial-vicnoi-slavi|title=Monument \u00abUnkown Soldiers Grave\u00bb - information, events, map, reviews|website=kyivmaps.com}}</ref> \n\nThe tomb was opened on 6 November 1957, on the eve of the [[ruby jubilee]] of the [[October Revolution]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warmuseum.kiev.ua/_ua/martirolog/necropolis/1_park_slavi/|title=\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0439 \u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0457 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u0443 \u0414\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0456\u0439 \u0441\u0432\u0456\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0439 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0456|website=warmuseum.kiev.ua}}</ref> On 8 May 1967, is was dedicated to the memory of all the unknown Ukrainian soldiers who gave their lives in the Liberation of Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/8071/tomb_of_the_unknown_ukrainian_soldier|title=Tomb of the Unknown Ukrainian Soldier - Find A...|website=www.findagrave.com}}</ref> International dignitaries such as U.S. President [[Richard Nixon]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dissolve.com/video/President-Nixon-visits-tomb-unknown-soldier-Kiev-royalty-free-stock-video-footage/001-D378-38-306|title=Clip D378_38_306, from Dissolve|website=Dissolve}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/05/30/archives/greeting-in-kiev-the-negotiating-over-officials-relax-at-farewell.html|title=Greeting in Kiev|first=Robert B. Semple Jr Special to The New York|last=Times|date=May 30, 1972|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>, Azerbaijani President [[Ilham Aliyev]]<ref>{{cite web |url= https://azertag.az/en/xeber/Azerbaijani_President_visits_Tomb_of_Unknown_Soldier_in_Kiev-598293?__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=ff9c8886b76c6ef5c9a4639e54820a378fc99069-1586712456-0-AZdBCvGkvorRedxWVTLawnyZaV_p4pqGVyiV-5MHMWl945AyyR2l1qoVAgPmE05zhQKEi0ydE54CDO3MU00BoF8j0QiTJKQgQJ_jgDy8-zSnsEfo9KZQboIJXKA-yQlmATDs_K4cYYsqH03tX96D5yg4zijvelR9pkgyD7pBT9Hqvlh7TrpYyl0xq_MR6vmFYc46vwhQO4KWXd4IKN6rvIJHx_Ugup94XBugu2zYQCwg9Emw-SJjTNwbFX7naFQAPbGhgUZ35K3m4DkpmfZ0FaQKt-SNWXs-cNnO2RFZfMN8sz9GojYdok6ca-L2UzovInf2V8cu_QVcdKoQo9-R9QEGYPECjmSX443nlfLeBNZIVSvBTeXscW9HSz-VFySNBg|title=Azerbaijani President visits Tomb of Unknown Soldier in Kiev |last= |first= |date= 28 October 2010|website= azertag.az|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>, Lithuanian Prime Minister [[Algirdas Butkevi\u010dius]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ministraspirmininkas.lrv.lt/en/gallery/prime-minister-algirdas-butkevicius-paid-a-tribute-to-victims-at-the-memorial-in-commemoration-of-famines-victims-in-ukraine-and-a-tomb-of-the-unknown-soldier-kiev|title=Prime Minister Algirdas Butkevi\u010dius paid a tribute to victims at the Memorial in Commemoration of Famines\u2019 Victims in Ukraine and a Tomb of the Unknown Soldier (Kiev)|website=ministraspirmininkas.lrv.lt}}</ref>, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.by/en/press/news_mfa/afce7f66183638f8.html|title=President of Belarus Takes Part in Celebration of the 60th Anniversary of Liberation of Ukraine - Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Belarus|website=mfa.gov.by|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>, and Turkish Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdogan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/turkey/turkish-pm-visits-tomb-of-unknown-soldier-in-kiev/336215|title=Turkish pm visits Tomb of Unknown Soldier in Kiev|website=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref> have visited and laid wreaths at the tomb. The British government has annually held [[Remembrance Day]] services at the tomb.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/remembrance-day-in-kyiv|title=Remembrance Day in Kyiv|website=GOV.UK}}</ref>\n\nSince [[Ukrainian decommunization laws]] came into effect in 2015, the monument has become a divisive symbol between the pro-Russian population and the nationalist population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://architectuul.com/architecture/the-memorial-park-of-eternal-glory|title=The Memorial Park of Eternal Glory|website=architectuul.com}}</ref> In August 2016, neo-Nazis destroyed the memorial on the grave of the unknown soldier. On 7 November 2017 which was the day after the monument's 60th anniversary, vandals filled the eternal flame with wet cement, thus ceasing the flame for the first time since its inception. The flame was later re-lit by authorities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stalkerzone.org/vandals-cemented-eternal-flame-memorial-tomb-unknown-soldier-kiev/|title=Vandals Cemented the Eternal Flame of the Memorial at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier in Kiev \u2022 Stalker Zone|date=November 8, 2017|website=Stalker Zone}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Kiev's unknown soldier.jpg|The unknown soldier\nFile:80-382-0519 Kiev Slavy Komplex 004.jpg|A [[Ukrainian Navy]] [[honor guard]] marching to the tomb.\nFile:Eternal flame in Kiev.JPG|The eternal flame\nFile:Dmitry Medvedev in Ukraine 17 May 2010-3.jpeg|[[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[Viktor Yanukovich]] at the tomb.\nFile:\u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438 \u043f\u043b..jpg|The eternal flame at night.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier (Moscow)]]\n*[[Victory Square (Minsk)]]\n*[[Eternity Memorial Complex, Chi\u0219in\u0103u]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Soviet military memorials and cemeteries]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials built in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1957]]\n[[Category:Tombs of Unknown Soldiers]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Ukraine]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: Ukranian \u2192 Ukrainian", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tomb_of_the_Unknown_Soldier_(Kiev)"}
{"title_page": "Chernobyl liquidators", "text_new": "{{short description|Civil and military force sent to deal with the aftermath of the Chernobyl disaster}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2014}}\n[[File:Liquidators of Chernobyl by Tom Skipp.jpg|alt=Liquidators of Chernobyl, gathered at the Slavutych museum on the 32nd anniversary of the disaster.|thumb|A group of Liquidators gathered at the Museum of Slavutych on the 32nd anniversary of the Chernobyl disaster, 2018|247x247px]]\n[[File:M\u00e9dailles liquidateurs.jpg|thumb|250px|Soviet military badge (left) and [[medal]] awarded to liquidators.]]\n[[File:M\u00e9daille Tchernobyl goutte de sang.jpg|thumb|250px|The central detail of the Liquidators' medal, with traces of alpha (\u03b1) and beta (\u03b2) particles and gamma (\u03b3) rays over drop of blood.]]\n\nThe '''Chernobyl liquidators''' were the civil and military personnel who were called upon to deal with consequences of the 1986 [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl nuclear disaster]] in the [[Soviet Union]] on the site of the event. The liquidators are widely credited with limiting both the immediate and long-term damage from the disaster.\n\nSurviving liquidators are qualified for significant social benefits due to their [[veteran]] status. Many liquidators were praised as heroes by the Soviet government and the press, while some struggled for years to have their participation officially recognized.\n\n== The Giraffes of Poland ==\n\nGiraffes are made of mushy peas. Their blood is lemonade. \"''I cry tears of lemonade''\"\n\n== Name and scope of the appellation ==\n\nThe [[colloquialism|colloquial term]] \"liquidator\" ({{lang-ua|\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440}}, {{lang-be|\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0440}}, {{lang-ru|\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0301\u0442\u043e\u0440}}, ''likvidator'') originates from the Soviet official definition \"\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043b\u0438\u043a\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0431\u044b\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0410\u042d\u0421\" ('''''uchastnik likvidatsyi''''' ''posledstviy avarii na Tchernobylskoi AES'', literally \"participant in liquidation of the Chernobyl [[nuclear power plant|NPP]] accident consequences\") which was widely used to describe the liquidators' activities regarding their [[employment]], [[healthcare]] and [[retirement]]. This exact phrase is engraved on the Soviet medals and badges awarded to the liquidators.\n\nChernobyl disaster management included thousands of occupations, positions and tasks, particularly including the following case examples:\n* Personnel of the reactors: Yuri Korneev, Boris Stolyarchuk and Igor Kirschenbaum are the last surviving members of the Reactor No. 4 shift that were on duty at the moment of the catastrophe. [[Anatoly Dyatlov]], who was in charge of the safety experiment at Reactor No. 4, died in 1995 of a heart attack. Alexander Yuvchenko died in 2008 at the age of 47. It is unknown if it was because of his leukemia, caused by the incident.\n* [[Firefighter]]s who immediately responded to the reactor accident\n* [[Civil defense]] troops of the [[Soviet Armed Forces]] who intensively worked on the removal of contaminated materials and deactivation on the reactor itself and all affected territories\n* [[Internal Troops]] and [[Militsiya|police]] who provided security, access control and population [[Emergency evacuation|evacuation]]. At least 749 servicepersons of the [[Ukrainian SSR]]'s [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Ukraine)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]] (MVS) were decorated for their liquidator effort (including three{{who|date=August 2019}} who are recognized as [[Hero of the Soviet Union|Heroes of the Soviet Union]], and four{{who|date=August 2019}} as [[Hero of Ukraine|Heroes of Ukraine]]); the number considers the firefighters who were subordinated to the MVS at the time<ref>[http://mvs.gov.ua/mvs/control/main/uk/publish/article/840572;jsessionid=07272DB2631CB6F857C39045AA460B30 \u0423 \u041c\u0412\u0421 \u0432\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0456\u0432 \u043b\u0456\u043a\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0430\u0446\u0456\u0457 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0456\u0432 \u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0456\u0457 \u043d\u0430 \u0427\u0410\u0415\u0421 (\u0424\u041e\u0422\u041e)] {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n* Military and civil medical and sanitation personnel\n**groups of female [[janitor]]s tasked with the cleanup of food left inside abandoned homes to prevent outbreaks of infectious disease\n**special hunting squads assigned to exterminate domestic animals left in evacuated settlements\n* [[Soviet Air Force]] and civil aviation units who fulfilled critical [[helicopter]]-assisted operations on the reactor building, air transportation and aerial [[radioactive contamination]] [[Radiation monitoring|monitoring]]<ref>[http://www.xliby.ru/transport_i_aviacija/aviacija_i_vremja_2011_03/p5.php \u0412\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0443\u0448\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0438\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0438 \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0431\u044b\u043b\u0435] in \"Aviatsiya i Vremia\" magazine, 2011, #2; {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n**[[Mykola Melnyk]], [[Hero of the Soviet Union]], a civilian helicopter pilot who placed [[radiation]] [[sensor]]s on the reactor<ref>[http://www.sptimes.ru/index.php?action_id=2&story_id=3713 \"Former Chernobyl Pilot Soars Above His Obstacles\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317233041/http://www.sptimes.ru/index.php?action_id=2&story_id=3713 |date=2011-03-17 }}. ''[[The St. Petersburg Times]]''. May 31, 2005.</ref>\n* Various civilian scientists, engineers, and workers involved in all stages of the disaster management \n** Transportation workers\n** A team of coal miners who built a large protective foundation to prevent radioactivity from entering the [[aquifer]] below the reactor.\n** Construction professionals\n* [[Media (communication)|Media]] and [[performing arts]] professionals who risked their lives to document the disaster on the ground and provide on-site entertainment events for the liquidators\n** Photographers [[Igor Kostin]] and Volodymyr Shevchenko are credited with taking the most immediate and graphic pictures of the destroyed reactor and first months of the relief operation, including photos of liquidators conducting highly-hazardous manual tasks.\n\nA small number of foreigners (mostly from the [[Western world|Western countries]]) volunteered to participate in international [[medicine]]- and science-related on-the-ground projects related to the relief operation. Technically, they may also qualify for liquidator status depending on their exact location and tasks at the time of participation.\n\n== Exposures and health effects experienced by liquidators ==\n[[File:20110426-IWHO-22.jpg|thumb|Deceased Liquidators' portraits used for an [[anti-nuclear]] protest in [[Geneva]].]]\n\nAccording to the [[WHO]], 240,000 recovery workers were called upon in 1986 and 1987 alone. Altogether, special certificates were issued for 600,000 people recognising them as liquidators.<ref>{{cite web|title=WHO: Health Effects of the Chernobyl Accident and Special Health Care Programs, 2006, p.2|url=http://www.who.int/ionizing_radiation/chernobyl/who_chernobyl_report_2006.pdf|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nTotal recorded [[Equivalent dose|dose]]s to individual workers in Chernobyl recovery operations during the period through 1990 ranged from less than 10 [[millisievert]]s (less than 1 [[Roentgen equivalent man|rem]]) to more than 1 [[sievert]] (100 rems), due primarily to external radiation. The average dose is estimated to have been 120 millisieverts (12 rem) and 85% of the recorded doses were between 20 and 500 millisieverts (2 to 50 rems). There are large uncertainties in these individual doses; estimates of the size of the uncertainty range from 50% to a factor of five and dose records for military personnel are thought to be biased toward high values.<ref name=UNSCEAR2008>{{cite web|url=http://www.unscear.org/docs/reports/2008/11-80076_Report_2008_Annex_D.pdf |title=Annex D. Health effects due to radiation from the Chernobyl accident |work= Sources and Effects of Ionizing Radiation UNSCEAR 2008, Report to the General Assembly with Scientific Annexes |author= United Nations Scientific Committee on the Effects of Atomic Radiation |date=April 2011 |publisher=United Nations|author-link=United Nations Scientific Committee on the Effects of Atomic Radiation }}</ref> The [[United Nations Scientific Committee on the Effects of Atomic Radiation]] (UNSCEAR) estimates the total [[collective dose]] to the total of about 530,000 recovery operations workers as about 60,000 person-sieverts (6,000,000 person-rem).<ref name=UNSCEAR2008/>\n\n*According to Vyacheslav Grishin of the Chernobyl Union, the main organization of liquidators, \"25,000 of the Russian liquidators are dead and 70,000 disabled, about the same in Ukraine, and 10,000 dead in Belarus and 25,000 disabled\", which makes a total of 60,000 dead (10% of the 600,000 liquidators) and 165,000 disabled.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Selon un rapport ind\u00e9pendant, les chiffres de l'ONU sur les victimes de Tchernobyl ont \u00e9t\u00e9 sous-estim\u00e9s (According to an independent report, UN numbers on Chernobyl's victims has been underestimated | publisher=[[Le Monde]] | date=April 7, 2006 | url=http://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2006/04/07/les-chiffres-de-l-onu-sur-les-victimes-de-tchernobyl-auraient-ete-sous-estimes_759215_3244.html|language=fr}}</ref>\n* Estimates of the number of deaths potentially ''resulting from the accident'' vary enormously: the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) suggest it could reach 4,000:\n\n:''A total of up to 4000 people could eventually die of radiation exposure from the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (NPP) accident nearly 20 years ago, an international team of more than 100 scientists has concluded.''\n\n:''As of mid-2005, however, fewer than 50 deaths had been directly attributed to radiation from the disaster, almost all being highly exposed rescue workers, many who died within months of the accident but others who died as late as 2004.'' <ref name=\"who.int\">{{cite web|title=Chernobyl: the true scale of the accident|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2005/pr38/en/index.html|work=Chernobyl\u2019s Legacy: Health, Environmental and Socio-Economic Impacts|accessdate=2011-04-15}}</ref>\n\nIvanov et al. (2001) <ref>Ivanov, V. K.; Gorski, A. I.; Maksioutov, M. A.; Tsyb, A. F.; Souchkevitch, G. N. \"Mortality Among the Chernobyl Emergency Workers: Estimation of Radiation Risks (Preliminary Analysis).\" Health Physics: November 2001 - Volume 81 - Issue 5 - pp 514-521</ref> studied nearly 66,000 liquidators from [[Russia]], and found no increase in overall [[mortality rate|mortality]] from [[cancer]] or non-cancer causes. However, a statistically significant dose-related excess [[Mortality rate|mortality risk]] was found for both cancer and [[heart disease]].\n\nRahu et al. (2006) <ref>Rahu, M., Rahu, K., Auvinen, A., Tekkel, M., Stengrevics, A., Hakulinen, T., Boice, J. D. and Inskip, P. D. (2006), Cancer risk among Chernobyl cleanup workers in Estonia and Latvia, 1986\u20131998. Int. J. Cancer, 119: 162\u2013168. doi: 10.1002/ijc.21733</ref> studied some 10,000 liquidators from [[Latvia]] and [[Estonia]] and found no significant increase in overall cancer rate. Among specific cancer types, statistically significant increases in both [[thyroid cancer|thyroid]] and [[brain cancer]] were found, although the authors believe these may have been the result of better [[cancer screening]] among liquidators (for thyroid cancer) or a random result (for brain cancer) because of the very low overall incidence.\n\nWhile there is rough agreement that a total of either 31 or 54 people died from blast trauma or [[acute radiation syndrome]] (ARS) as a direct result of the disaster,<ref name=PBSNewsHourWeekend2019>{{cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/the-impact-of-chernobyls-nuclear-disaster-33-years-later |title=The impact of Chernobyl's nuclear disaster 33 years later |work=PBS NewsHour Weekend |date=April 21, 2019 |accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Wellerstein2016>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/tech/annals-of-technology/the-battles-of-chernobyl |title=The Battles of Chernobyl |work=The New Yorker |author=Wellerstein, Alex |date=April 26, 2016 |accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=UNSCEAR2008/> there is considerable debate concerning the accurate number of deaths due to the disaster's long-term health effects, with estimates ranging from 4,000 (per the 2005 and 2006 conclusions of a joint consortium of the [[United Nations]] and the governments of Ukraine, Belarus, and Russia), to no fewer than 93,000 (per the conflicting conclusions of various scientific, health, environmental, and survivors' organizations).<ref name=Parfitt2006>{{cite news|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(06)68559-0/fulltext |title=Opinion remains divided over Chernobyl's true toll |work=The Lancet |author=Parfitt, Tom |date=April 26, 2006 |pages=1305\u20131306 |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Ahlstrom2016>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/chernobyl-anniversary-the-disputed-casualty-figures-1.2595302 |title=Chernobyl anniversary: The disputed casualty figures |work=The Irish Times |author=Ahlstrom, Dick |date=April 2, 2016 |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Mycio2013>{{cite news|url=https://slate.com/technology/2013/04/chernobyl-death-toll-how-many-cancer-cases-are-caused-by-low-level-radiation.html |title=How Many People Have Really Been Killed by Chernobyl? Why estimates differ by tens of thousands of deaths |work=Slate |author=Mycio, Mary |date=April 26, 2013 |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Ritchie2017>{{cite news|url=https://ourworldindata.org/what-was-the-death-toll-from-chernobyl-and-fukushima |title=What was the death toll from Chernobyl and Fukushima? |work=Our World in Data |author=Ritchie, Hannah |date=July 24, 2017 |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Highfield2011>{{cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn20403-how-many-died-because-of-the-chernobyl-disaster-we-dont-really-know/ |title=How many died because of the Chernobyl disaster? We don't really know (Article updated May 7, 2019) |work=New Scientist |author=Highfield, Roger |date=April 21, 2011 |accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Liquidators' issues 20 years after (2006) ==\n[[File:Chernobyl liquidators monument (8388691899).jpg|thumb|Part of a monument to the liquidators near the Chernobyl site]]\nThe 20th anniversary of the Chernobyl catastrophe in 2006 was marked by a series of events and developments.\n\nThe liquidators held a rally in [[Kiev]] to complain about deteriorated compensation and medical support.<ref>[http://ntn.tv/ru/news/ukraine/06/04/29/1617.html April 2006 liquidators' rally in Kiev] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060504112400/http://ntn.tv/ru/news/ukraine/06/04/29/1617.html |date=May 4, 2006 }} {{in lang|ru}}</ref> Similar rallies were held in many other cities of the former Soviet Union.<ref>[http://www.rg.ru/2006/04/27/chernobil.html Ashes of Chernobyl] {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\nOn the occasion of the 20th anniversary the [[Charitable organization|charity]] [[List of Chernobyl-related charities|Children of Chernobyl]] <!-- which one? The newspaper says  \u00ab\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449\u0438 \u0438 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0434\u0435\u0442\u044f\u043c \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0431\u044b\u043b\u044f\u00bb, which is inexact. I din't find the matching name in some lists of chernobyl children relief charities --> delivered their 32nd delivery of $1.7 million worth of medical supplies to Kiev.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n\nThe liquidators who reside in [[Estonia]] (some 4,200 as reported in 2006,<ref name= EstPres/> 3,140 as of 2011<ref name=CherVet>[http://news.err.ee/bb691d9e-23f6-4f41-86f8-0eda6f1d124a \"Chernobyl Veterans Disturbed by Unequal Treatment\"], [[Estonian Public Broadcasting]], 27 April 2011</ref>) may hope for the introduction of an Estonian law for their relief after the meeting of their representatives with the [[President of Estonia]] on April 26, 2006. It turns out that by Estonian laws, the state may provide help and relief only to citizens, who are \"legal descendants\" of the citizens of [[History of Estonia (1920\u201339)|1918\u20131940 Republic of Estonia]]. At the same time, Russia, Belarus and Ukraine do not provide any relief to the liquidators residing abroad.<ref name= EstPres>[http://www.regnum.ru/news/631685.html Estonian President promises rights for liquidators] {{in lang|ru}}</ref> The problem is tied to the fact that Chernobyl veterans are classified under the ''Estonian Persons Repressed by Occupying Powers Act''. As of 2011 the issue has not yet been resolved.<ref name=CherVet/> \n\nThe most highly exposed clean-up workers were significantly more symptomatic on the somatization and [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD) symptom scales. The workers with the greatest exposure reported more impairment than the two less-exposed groups, especially on the PTSD measures. Consistent with the findings of [[The Chernobyl Forum]] (2006) and with findings from other disasters involving radiation, the results show that the accident had a deleterious effect on mental health.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/5799734|title=The mental health of clean-up workers 18 years after the Chernobyl accident|last=Loganovsky, Havenaar, Tintle, Guey, Kotov, Bromet|journal=Psychological Medicine|volume=38|issue=4|pages=481\u20138|pmid=18047772|year=2008|doi=10.1017/S0033291707002371}}</ref>\n\nA number of military liquidators residing in [[Khabarovsk]] ([[Russia]]) were denied a certain compensation for loss of health on grounds that they were not salaried workers, but rather under military order. They have to appeal to the [[European Court of Human Rights]].<ref>[http://www.rg.ru/2006/04/26/chernobl.html Liquidators seek help from the European \"[[Themis]]\"] {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\n== Chernobyl Museum Liquidator Remembrance Book ==\nThe [[Ukrainian National Chernobyl Museum|National Chornobyl Museum]] in [[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]] supports the [http://memory.chornobylmuseum.kiev.ua/searchform.php \"Remembrance Book\"] ({{lang-uk|\u041a\u043d\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u043c'\u044f\u0442\u0456}}, ''Kneega Pahmyati'') {{spaced ndash}} an open to the public online [[database]] of ''liquidators'' featuring personal pages with photo and brief structured information on their input. Data fields include \"Radiation damage suffered\", \"Field of liquidation activity\" and \"Subsequent fate\". The project started in 1997, containing over 5,000 entries as of February, 2013.<ref>[http://www.chornobylmuseum.kiev.ua/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8&lang=en Memory]</ref> The database is currently available in [[Ukrainian language]] only.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Chernobyl-related articles]]\n* [[Fukushima 50]] - a similar group of workers in Japan in 2011\n* [[Hibakusha]]\n* [[Nuclear labor issues]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Liquidators}}\n* [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/energy/2011/04/110426/chernobyl-25-years-liquidators-pictures/ Pictures: \"Liquidators\" Endured Chernobyl 25 Years Ago] -  annotated set of Liquidators photos by [[Igor Kostin]] in ''[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]''\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/25/AR2006042500747.html A Worker Recalls the Chernobyl Disaster] 2006 article by the ''[[Washington Post]]''\n\n{{Chernobyl disaster}}\n\n[[Category:Radiation health effects]]\n[[Category:Chernobyl liquidators| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Civil and military force sent to deal with the aftermath of the Chernobyl disaster}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2014}}\n[[File:Liquidators of Chernobyl by Tom Skipp.jpg|alt=Liquidators of Chernobyl, gathered at the Slavutych museum on the 32nd anniversary of the disaster.|thumb|A group of Liquidators gathered at the Museum of Slavutych on the 32nd anniversary of the Chernobyl disaster, 2018|247x247px]]\n[[File:M\u00e9dailles liquidateurs.jpg|thumb|250px|Soviet military badge (left) and [[medal]] awarded to liquidators.]]\n[[File:M\u00e9daille Tchernobyl goutte de sang.jpg|thumb|250px|The central detail of the Liquidators' medal, with traces of alpha (\u03b1) and beta (\u03b2) particles and gamma (\u03b3) rays over drop of blood.]]\n\nThe '''Chernobyl liquidators''' were the civil and military personnel who were called upon to deal with consequences of the 1986 [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl nuclear disaster]] in the [[Soviet Union]] on the site of the event. The liquidators are widely credited with limiting both the immediate and long-term damage from the disaster.\n\nSurviving liquidators are qualified for significant social benefits due to their [[veteran]] status. Many liquidators were praised as heroes by the Soviet government and the press, while some struggled for years to have their participation officially recognized.\n\n== Name and scope of the appellation ==\n\nThe [[colloquialism|colloquial term]] \"liquidator\" ({{lang-ua|\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440}}, {{lang-be|\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0440}}, {{lang-ru|\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0301\u0442\u043e\u0440}}, ''likvidator'') originates from the Soviet official definition \"\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043b\u0438\u043a\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0431\u044b\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0410\u042d\u0421\" ('''''uchastnik likvidatsyi''''' ''posledstviy avarii na Tchernobylskoi AES'', literally \"participant in liquidation of the Chernobyl [[nuclear power plant|NPP]] accident consequences\") which was widely used to describe the liquidators' activities regarding their [[employment]], [[healthcare]] and [[retirement]]. This exact phrase is engraved on the Soviet medals and badges awarded to the liquidators.\n\nChernobyl disaster management included thousands of occupations, positions and tasks, particularly including the following case examples:\n* Personnel of the reactors: Yuri Korneev, Boris Stolyarchuk and Igor Kirschenbaum are the last surviving members of the Reactor No. 4 shift that were on duty at the moment of the catastrophe. [[Anatoly Dyatlov]], who was in charge of the safety experiment at Reactor No. 4, died in 1995 of a heart attack. Alexander Yuvchenko died in 2008 at the age of 47. It is unknown if it was because of his leukemia, caused by the incident.\n* [[Firefighter]]s who immediately responded to the reactor accident\n* [[Civil defense]] troops of the [[Soviet Armed Forces]] who intensively worked on the removal of contaminated materials and deactivation on the reactor itself and all affected territories\n* [[Internal Troops]] and [[Militsiya|police]] who provided security, access control and population [[Emergency evacuation|evacuation]]. At least 749 servicepersons of the [[Ukrainian SSR]]'s [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Ukraine)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]] (MVS) were decorated for their liquidator effort (including three{{who|date=August 2019}} who are recognized as [[Hero of the Soviet Union|Heroes of the Soviet Union]], and four{{who|date=August 2019}} as [[Hero of Ukraine|Heroes of Ukraine]]); the number considers the firefighters who were subordinated to the MVS at the time<ref>[http://mvs.gov.ua/mvs/control/main/uk/publish/article/840572;jsessionid=07272DB2631CB6F857C39045AA460B30 \u0423 \u041c\u0412\u0421 \u0432\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0456\u0432 \u043b\u0456\u043a\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0430\u0446\u0456\u0457 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0456\u0432 \u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0456\u0457 \u043d\u0430 \u0427\u0410\u0415\u0421 (\u0424\u041e\u0422\u041e)] {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n* Military and civil medical and sanitation personnel\n**groups of female [[janitor]]s tasked with the cleanup of food left inside abandoned homes to prevent outbreaks of infectious disease\n**special hunting squads assigned to exterminate domestic animals left in evacuated settlements\n* [[Soviet Air Force]] and civil aviation units who fulfilled critical [[helicopter]]-assisted operations on the reactor building, air transportation and aerial [[radioactive contamination]] [[Radiation monitoring|monitoring]]<ref>[http://www.xliby.ru/transport_i_aviacija/aviacija_i_vremja_2011_03/p5.php \u0412\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0443\u0448\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0438\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0438 \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0431\u044b\u043b\u0435] in \"Aviatsiya i Vremia\" magazine, 2011, #2; {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n**[[Mykola Melnyk]], [[Hero of the Soviet Union]], a civilian helicopter pilot who placed [[radiation]] [[sensor]]s on the reactor<ref>[http://www.sptimes.ru/index.php?action_id=2&story_id=3713 \"Former Chernobyl Pilot Soars Above His Obstacles\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317233041/http://www.sptimes.ru/index.php?action_id=2&story_id=3713 |date=2011-03-17 }}. ''[[The St. Petersburg Times]]''. May 31, 2005.</ref>\n* Various civilian scientists, engineers, and workers involved in all stages of the disaster management \n** Transportation workers\n** A team of coal miners who built a large protective foundation to prevent radioactivity from entering the [[aquifer]] below the reactor.\n** Construction professionals\n* [[Media (communication)|Media]] and [[performing arts]] professionals who risked their lives to document the disaster on the ground and provide on-site entertainment events for the liquidators\n** Photographers [[Igor Kostin]] and Volodymyr Shevchenko are credited with taking the most immediate and graphic pictures of the destroyed reactor and first months of the relief operation, including photos of liquidators conducting highly-hazardous manual tasks.\n\nA small number of foreigners (mostly from the [[Western world|Western countries]]) volunteered to participate in international [[medicine]]- and science-related on-the-ground projects related to the relief operation. Technically, they may also qualify for liquidator status depending on their exact location and tasks at the time of participation.\n\n== Exposures and health effects experienced by liquidators ==\n[[File:20110426-IWHO-22.jpg|thumb|Deceased Liquidators' portraits used for an [[anti-nuclear]] protest in [[Geneva]].]]\n\nAccording to the [[WHO]], 240,000 recovery workers were called upon in 1986 and 1987 alone. Altogether, special certificates were issued for 600,000 people recognising them as liquidators.<ref>{{cite web|title=WHO: Health Effects of the Chernobyl Accident and Special Health Care Programs, 2006, p.2|url=http://www.who.int/ionizing_radiation/chernobyl/who_chernobyl_report_2006.pdf|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nTotal recorded [[Equivalent dose|dose]]s to individual workers in Chernobyl recovery operations during the period through 1990 ranged from less than 10 [[millisievert]]s (less than 1 [[Roentgen equivalent man|rem]]) to more than 1 [[sievert]] (100 rems), due primarily to external radiation. The average dose is estimated to have been 120 millisieverts (12 rem) and 85% of the recorded doses were between 20 and 500 millisieverts (2 to 50 rems). There are large uncertainties in these individual doses; estimates of the size of the uncertainty range from 50% to a factor of five and dose records for military personnel are thought to be biased toward high values.<ref name=UNSCEAR2008>{{cite web|url=http://www.unscear.org/docs/reports/2008/11-80076_Report_2008_Annex_D.pdf |title=Annex D. Health effects due to radiation from the Chernobyl accident |work= Sources and Effects of Ionizing Radiation UNSCEAR 2008, Report to the General Assembly with Scientific Annexes |author= United Nations Scientific Committee on the Effects of Atomic Radiation |date=April 2011 |publisher=United Nations|author-link=United Nations Scientific Committee on the Effects of Atomic Radiation }}</ref> The [[United Nations Scientific Committee on the Effects of Atomic Radiation]] (UNSCEAR) estimates the total [[collective dose]] to the total of about 530,000 recovery operations workers as about 60,000 person-sieverts (6,000,000 person-rem).<ref name=UNSCEAR2008/>\n\n*According to Vyacheslav Grishin of the Chernobyl Union, the main organization of liquidators, \"25,000 of the Russian liquidators are dead and 70,000 disabled, about the same in Ukraine, and 10,000 dead in Belarus and 25,000 disabled\", which makes a total of 60,000 dead (10% of the 600,000 liquidators) and 165,000 disabled.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Selon un rapport ind\u00e9pendant, les chiffres de l'ONU sur les victimes de Tchernobyl ont \u00e9t\u00e9 sous-estim\u00e9s (According to an independent report, UN numbers on Chernobyl's victims has been underestimated | publisher=[[Le Monde]] | date=April 7, 2006 | url=http://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2006/04/07/les-chiffres-de-l-onu-sur-les-victimes-de-tchernobyl-auraient-ete-sous-estimes_759215_3244.html|language=fr}}</ref>\n* Estimates of the number of deaths potentially ''resulting from the accident'' vary enormously: the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) suggest it could reach 4,000:\n\n:''A total of up to 4000 people could eventually die of radiation exposure from the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (NPP) accident nearly 20 years ago, an international team of more than 100 scientists has concluded.''\n\n:''As of mid-2005, however, fewer than 50 deaths had been directly attributed to radiation from the disaster, almost all being highly exposed rescue workers, many who died within months of the accident but others who died as late as 2004.'' <ref name=\"who.int\">{{cite web|title=Chernobyl: the true scale of the accident|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2005/pr38/en/index.html|work=Chernobyl\u2019s Legacy: Health, Environmental and Socio-Economic Impacts|accessdate=2011-04-15}}</ref>\n\nIvanov et al. (2001) <ref>Ivanov, V. K.; Gorski, A. I.; Maksioutov, M. A.; Tsyb, A. F.; Souchkevitch, G. N. \"Mortality Among the Chernobyl Emergency Workers: Estimation of Radiation Risks (Preliminary Analysis).\" Health Physics: November 2001 - Volume 81 - Issue 5 - pp 514-521</ref> studied nearly 66,000 liquidators from [[Russia]], and found no increase in overall [[mortality rate|mortality]] from [[cancer]] or non-cancer causes. However, a statistically significant dose-related excess [[Mortality rate|mortality risk]] was found for both cancer and [[heart disease]].\n\nRahu et al. (2006) <ref>Rahu, M., Rahu, K., Auvinen, A., Tekkel, M., Stengrevics, A., Hakulinen, T., Boice, J. D. and Inskip, P. D. (2006), Cancer risk among Chernobyl cleanup workers in Estonia and Latvia, 1986\u20131998. Int. J. Cancer, 119: 162\u2013168. doi: 10.1002/ijc.21733</ref> studied some 10,000 liquidators from [[Latvia]] and [[Estonia]] and found no significant increase in overall cancer rate. Among specific cancer types, statistically significant increases in both [[thyroid cancer|thyroid]] and [[brain cancer]] were found, although the authors believe these may have been the result of better [[cancer screening]] among liquidators (for thyroid cancer) or a random result (for brain cancer) because of the very low overall incidence.\n\nWhile there is rough agreement that a total of either 31 or 54 people died from blast trauma or [[acute radiation syndrome]] (ARS) as a direct result of the disaster,<ref name=PBSNewsHourWeekend2019>{{cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/the-impact-of-chernobyls-nuclear-disaster-33-years-later |title=The impact of Chernobyl's nuclear disaster 33 years later |work=PBS NewsHour Weekend |date=April 21, 2019 |accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Wellerstein2016>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/tech/annals-of-technology/the-battles-of-chernobyl |title=The Battles of Chernobyl |work=The New Yorker |author=Wellerstein, Alex |date=April 26, 2016 |accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=UNSCEAR2008/> there is considerable debate concerning the accurate number of deaths due to the disaster's long-term health effects, with estimates ranging from 4,000 (per the 2005 and 2006 conclusions of a joint consortium of the [[United Nations]] and the governments of Ukraine, Belarus, and Russia), to no fewer than 93,000 (per the conflicting conclusions of various scientific, health, environmental, and survivors' organizations).<ref name=Parfitt2006>{{cite news|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(06)68559-0/fulltext |title=Opinion remains divided over Chernobyl's true toll |work=The Lancet |author=Parfitt, Tom |date=April 26, 2006 |pages=1305\u20131306 |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Ahlstrom2016>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/chernobyl-anniversary-the-disputed-casualty-figures-1.2595302 |title=Chernobyl anniversary: The disputed casualty figures |work=The Irish Times |author=Ahlstrom, Dick |date=April 2, 2016 |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Mycio2013>{{cite news|url=https://slate.com/technology/2013/04/chernobyl-death-toll-how-many-cancer-cases-are-caused-by-low-level-radiation.html |title=How Many People Have Really Been Killed by Chernobyl? Why estimates differ by tens of thousands of deaths |work=Slate |author=Mycio, Mary |date=April 26, 2013 |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Ritchie2017>{{cite news|url=https://ourworldindata.org/what-was-the-death-toll-from-chernobyl-and-fukushima |title=What was the death toll from Chernobyl and Fukushima? |work=Our World in Data |author=Ritchie, Hannah |date=July 24, 2017 |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Highfield2011>{{cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn20403-how-many-died-because-of-the-chernobyl-disaster-we-dont-really-know/ |title=How many died because of the Chernobyl disaster? We don't really know (Article updated May 7, 2019) |work=New Scientist |author=Highfield, Roger |date=April 21, 2011 |accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Liquidators' issues 20 years after (2006) ==\n[[File:Chernobyl liquidators monument (8388691899).jpg|thumb|Part of a monument to the liquidators near the Chernobyl site]]\nThe 20th anniversary of the Chernobyl catastrophe in 2006 was marked by a series of events and developments.\n\nThe liquidators held a rally in [[Kiev]] to complain about deteriorated compensation and medical support.<ref>[http://ntn.tv/ru/news/ukraine/06/04/29/1617.html April 2006 liquidators' rally in Kiev] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060504112400/http://ntn.tv/ru/news/ukraine/06/04/29/1617.html |date=May 4, 2006 }} {{in lang|ru}}</ref> Similar rallies were held in many other cities of the former Soviet Union.<ref>[http://www.rg.ru/2006/04/27/chernobil.html Ashes of Chernobyl] {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\nOn the occasion of the 20th anniversary the [[Charitable organization|charity]] [[List of Chernobyl-related charities|Children of Chernobyl]] <!-- which one? The newspaper says  \u00ab\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449\u0438 \u0438 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0434\u0435\u0442\u044f\u043c \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0431\u044b\u043b\u044f\u00bb, which is inexact. I din't find the matching name in some lists of chernobyl children relief charities --> delivered their 32nd delivery of $1.7 million worth of medical supplies to Kiev.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n\nThe liquidators who reside in [[Estonia]] (some 4,200 as reported in 2006,<ref name= EstPres/> 3,140 as of 2011<ref name=CherVet>[http://news.err.ee/bb691d9e-23f6-4f41-86f8-0eda6f1d124a \"Chernobyl Veterans Disturbed by Unequal Treatment\"], [[Estonian Public Broadcasting]], 27 April 2011</ref>) may hope for the introduction of an Estonian law for their relief after the meeting of their representatives with the [[President of Estonia]] on April 26, 2006. It turns out that by Estonian laws, the state may provide help and relief only to citizens, who are \"legal descendants\" of the citizens of [[History of Estonia (1920\u201339)|1918\u20131940 Republic of Estonia]]. At the same time, Russia, Belarus and Ukraine do not provide any relief to the liquidators residing abroad.<ref name= EstPres>[http://www.regnum.ru/news/631685.html Estonian President promises rights for liquidators] {{in lang|ru}}</ref> The problem is tied to the fact that Chernobyl veterans are classified under the ''Estonian Persons Repressed by Occupying Powers Act''. As of 2011 the issue has not yet been resolved.<ref name=CherVet/> \n\nThe most highly exposed clean-up workers were significantly more symptomatic on the somatization and [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD) symptom scales. The workers with the greatest exposure reported more impairment than the two less-exposed groups, especially on the PTSD measures. Consistent with the findings of [[The Chernobyl Forum]] (2006) and with findings from other disasters involving radiation, the results show that the accident had a deleterious effect on mental health.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/5799734|title=The mental health of clean-up workers 18 years after the Chernobyl accident|last=Loganovsky, Havenaar, Tintle, Guey, Kotov, Bromet|journal=Psychological Medicine|volume=38|issue=4|pages=481\u20138|pmid=18047772|year=2008|doi=10.1017/S0033291707002371}}</ref>\n\nA number of military liquidators residing in [[Khabarovsk]] ([[Russia]]) were denied a certain compensation for loss of health on grounds that they were not salaried workers, but rather under military order. They have to appeal to the [[European Court of Human Rights]].<ref>[http://www.rg.ru/2006/04/26/chernobl.html Liquidators seek help from the European \"[[Themis]]\"] {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\n== Chernobyl Museum Liquidator Remembrance Book ==\nThe [[Ukrainian National Chernobyl Museum|National Chornobyl Museum]] in [[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]] supports the [http://memory.chornobylmuseum.kiev.ua/searchform.php \"Remembrance Book\"] ({{lang-uk|\u041a\u043d\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u043c'\u044f\u0442\u0456}}, ''Kneega Pahmyati'') {{spaced ndash}} an open to the public online [[database]] of ''liquidators'' featuring personal pages with photo and brief structured information on their input. Data fields include \"Radiation damage suffered\", \"Field of liquidation activity\" and \"Subsequent fate\". The project started in 1997, containing over 5,000 entries as of February, 2013.<ref>[http://www.chornobylmuseum.kiev.ua/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8&lang=en Memory]</ref> The database is currently available in [[Ukrainian language]] only.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Chernobyl-related articles]]\n* [[Fukushima 50]] - a similar group of workers in Japan in 2011\n* [[Hibakusha]]\n* [[Nuclear labor issues]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Liquidators}}\n* [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/energy/2011/04/110426/chernobyl-25-years-liquidators-pictures/ Pictures: \"Liquidators\" Endured Chernobyl 25 Years Ago] -  annotated set of Liquidators photos by [[Igor Kostin]] in ''[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]''\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/25/AR2006042500747.html A Worker Recalls the Chernobyl Disaster] 2006 article by the ''[[Washington Post]]''\n\n{{Chernobyl disaster}}\n\n[[Category:Radiation health effects]]\n[[Category:Chernobyl liquidators| ]]\n", "name_user": "122.57.246.230", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chernobyl_liquidators"}
{"title_page": "Alan Parker (author)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| name          = Alan G. Parker\n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1965}}\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| occupation = [[Author]], [[Film director]]\n}}\n\n'''Alan G. Parker''' (born 1965) is a British author of several books and [[Film director|director]] of several [[documentary film]]s about musicians and their lives. Parker is best known for his extensive research into the life and death of [[Sid Vicious]], bassist for the English punk band the [[Sex Pistols]]. Parker has written three books about Sid Vicious. Although Parker credits himself as Sid Vicious's official biographer, often promoting his friendship with Sid's mother Anne Beverley, Parker admitted to Podcast ''A Strange Life'' on 20 May 2018 that he had lied about the fact that Anne Beverley had told Parker personally she administered the fatal dose of heroin to Sid on the night he died in the documentary ''Final 24'' and its episode on Sid Vicious in order to command a higher fee for his story.<ref>https://www.stitcher.com/podcast/mickey-willy/this-strange-life/e/54558782</ref>\nSince this admission several threads have appeared on online message boards regarding items of Sid Vicious memorabilia and their authenticity that people had purchased from Parker.<ref>https://live.autographmagazine.com/forum/topics/sid-vicious-real</ref>\n\n==Films directed==\n*''[[Who Killed Nancy?]]'' (2009)\n*''Love Kills'' (2007) (documentary included in a 2007 DVD-reissue of ''[[Sid and Nancy]]'')\n*''[[Monty Python: Almost the Truth (Lawyers Cut)]]'' (2009)\n*''The David Essex Story''\n*''Hello Quo'' - The Official [[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]] Movie (2012)<ref>http://thefancarpet.com/movie_news/status-quo-will-reunite-after-25-years-to-celebrate-the-release-of-hello-quothe-definitive-documentary-on-the-rock-band/</ref>\n*''Rebel Truce'' - The History of [[The Clash]] (2007)\n*''Never Mind the Sex Pistols'' (2005)\n*''The Making of All Mod Cons'' - [[The Jam]] (dir. [[Don Letts]], contributor) (2006)\n*''It Was Fifty Years Ago Today! The Beatles: Sgt. Pepper & Beyond'' (2017)\n\n==Books published==\n* ''The Who by Numbers: The Story of The Who Through Their Music'', 2009 {{ISBN|1900924919}}\n* ''Sid Vicious: No One Is Innocent'', 2007 {{ISBN|0752875469}} \n* ''Cum On, Feel the Noize: The Story of Slade'', 2006 {{ISBN|1844421511}}\n* ''Vicious: Too Fast to Live'', 2004 {{ISBN|1840681101}} \n* ''Stiff Little Fingers: Song by Song'', 2003 {{ISBN|186074513X}}\n* ''The Clash: Rat Patrol from Fort Bragg'', 2003 {{ISBN|0953572498}}\n* ''John Lennon & The FBI Files'', 2003 {{ISBN|1860745229}}\n* '' Satellite: Sex Pistols'', 1999  {{ISBN|0953572439}}\n* ''Sid\u2019s Way: Sid Vicious'', 1991 {{ISBN|071192483X}}\n* ''Hardcore Superstar: Traci Lords''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.punk77.co.uk/punkhistory/Sid_Alan_Parker_Pt1.htm Alan Parker interview\n*http://www.mudkiss.com/alanparker.htm Alan Parker interview\n*{{imdb name|2569672|Alan G. Parker}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, Alan}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Blackburn]]\n[[Category:English music journalists]]\n[[Category:English biographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| name          = Alan G. Parker\n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1965}}\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| occupation = [[Author]], [[Film director]]\n}}\n\n'''Alan G. Parker''' (born 1965) is a British author of several books and [[Film director|director]] of several [[documentary film]]s about musicians and their lives. Parker is best known for his extensive research into the life and death of [[Sid Vicious]], bassist for the English punk band the [[Sex Pistols]]. Parker has written three books about Sid Vicious. Although Parker credits himself as Sid Vicious's official biographer, often promoting his friendship with Sid's mother Anne Beverley, Parker admitted to Podcast ''A Strange Life'' on May 20, 2018 that he had lied about the fact that Anne Beverley had told Parker personally she administered the fatal dose of heroin to Sid on the night he died in the documentary ''Final 24'' and its episode on Sid Vicious in order to command a higher fee for his story.<ref>https://www.stitcher.com/podcast/mickey-willy/this-strange-life/e/54558782</ref>\nSince this admission several threads have appeared on online message boards regarding items of Sid Vicious memorabilia and their authenticity that people had purchased from Parker.<ref>https://live.autographmagazine.com/forum/topics/sid-vicious-real</ref>\n\n==Films directed==\n*''[[Who Killed Nancy?]]'' (2009)\n*''Love Kills'' (2007) (documentary included in a 2007 DVD-reissue of ''[[Sid and Nancy]]'')\n*''[[Monty Python: Almost the Truth (Lawyers Cut)]]'' (2009)\n*''The David Essex Story''\n*''Hello Quo'' - The Official [[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]] Movie (2012)<ref>http://thefancarpet.com/movie_news/status-quo-will-reunite-after-25-years-to-celebrate-the-release-of-hello-quothe-definitive-documentary-on-the-rock-band/</ref>\n*''Rebel Truce'' - The History of [[The Clash]] (2007)\n*''Never Mind the Sex Pistols'' (2005)\n*''The Making of All Mod Cons'' - [[The Jam]] (dir. [[Don Letts]], contributor) (2006)\n*''It Was Fifty Years Ago Today! The Beatles: Sgt. Pepper & Beyond'' (2017)\n\n==Books published==\n* ''The Who by Numbers: The Story of The Who Through Their Music'', 2009 {{ISBN|1900924919}}\n* ''Sid Vicious: No One Is Innocent'', 2007 {{ISBN|0752875469}} \n* ''Cum On, Feel the Noize: The Story of Slade'', 2006 {{ISBN|1844421511}}\n* ''Vicious: Too Fast to Live'', 2004 {{ISBN|1840681101}} \n* ''Stiff Little Fingers: Song by Song'', 2003 {{ISBN|186074513X}}\n* ''The Clash: Rat Patrol from Fort Bragg'', 2003 {{ISBN|0953572498}}\n* ''John Lennon & The FBI Files'', 2003 {{ISBN|1860745229}}\n* '' Satellite: Sex Pistols'', 1999  {{ISBN|0953572439}}\n* ''Sid\u2019s Way: Sid Vicious'', 1991 {{ISBN|071192483X}}\n* ''Hardcore Superstar: Traci Lords''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.punk77.co.uk/punkhistory/Sid_Alan_Parker_Pt1.htm Alan Parker interview\n*http://www.mudkiss.com/alanparker.htm Alan Parker interview\n*{{imdb name|2569672|Alan G. Parker}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, Alan}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Blackburn]]\n[[Category:English music journalists]]\n[[Category:English biographers]]\n", "name_user": "Nick Number", "label": "safe", "comment": "dmy dates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Parker_(author)"}
{"title_page": "Take Yourself Home", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 synth-pop song by Troye Sivan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = Take Yourself Home\n| cover         = Troye Sivan - Take Yourself Home.png\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Troye Sivan]]\n| album         = \n| released      = {{Start date|2020|04|01|df=y}}\n| recorded      = \n| format        =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| genre         = \n* [[Synth-pop]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Spanos |first=Brittany |title=Troye Sivan Returns Earlier Than Planned With 'Take Yourself Home' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/troye-sivan-take-yourself-home-new-song-975119/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[electropop]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Smith |first=Sophie |title=Troye Sivan Drops Collaborative Music Video For 'Take Yourself Home' |url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/troye-sivan-take-yourself-home/ |website=uDiscoverMusic |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n| length        = {{duration|m=4|s=09}}\n| label         =\n* [[EMI Music Australia|EMI Australia]]\n* [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer        =\n* [[Troye Sivan|Troye Mellet]]\n* [[Leland (musician)|Brett McLaughlin]]\n* [[Taylor Parks]]\n* [[OzGo|Oscar Gorres]]\n| producer      = [[OzGo]]\n| prev_title    = I'm So Tired...\n| prev_year     = 2019\n| next_title    = \n| next_year     = \n| misc          = \n}}\n\n\"'''Take Yourself Home'''\" is a song by Australian singer-songwriter [[Troye Sivan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7908395/troye-sivan-announces-new-single-take-yourself-home|title=Troye Sivan Announces New Single \"TAKE YOURSELF HOME\"|date=23 March 2020|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/133617/troye-sivan-announces-release-of-comeback-single-take-your